# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: explosion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In 1257, a catastrophic eruption occurred at Samalas, a volcano on the Indonesian island of Lombok.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The event had a probable Volcanic Explosivity Index of 7, making it one of the largest volcanic eruptions during the Holocene epoch.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] It left behind a large caldera that contains Lake Segara Anak.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Later volcanic activity created more volcanic centres in the caldera, including the Barujari cone, which remains active.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The event created eruption columns reaching tens of kilometres into the atmosphere and pyroclastic flows that buried much of Lombok and crossed the sea to reach the neighbouring island of Sumbawa.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The flows destroyed human habitations, including the city of Pamatan, which was the capital of a kingdom on Lombok.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Ash from the eruption fell as far as 340 kilometres (210 mi) away in Java; the volcano deposited more than 10 cubic kilometres (2.4 cu mi) of rocks and ash.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The aerosols injected into the atmosphere reduced the solar radiation reaching the Earth's surface, causing a volcanic winter and cooling the atmosphere for several years.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] This led to famines and crop failures in Europe and elsewhere, although the exact scale of the temperature anomalies and their consequences is still debated.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption may have helped trigger the Little Ice Age, a centuries-long cold period during the last thousand years.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Before the site of the eruption was known, an examination of ice cores around the world had detected a large spike in sulfate deposition from around 1257 providing strong evidence of a large volcanic eruption occurring at that time.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In 2013, scientists linked the historical records about Mount Samalas to these spikes.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] These records were written by people who witnessed the event and recorded it on the *Babad Lombok*, a document written on palm leaves.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Samalas (also known as *Rinjani Tua*) was part of what is now the Rinjani volcanic complex, on Lombok, in Indonesia.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The remains of the volcano form the Segara Anak caldera, with Mount Rinjani at its eastern edge.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Since the destruction of Samalas, two new volcanoes, Rombongan and Barujari, have formed in the caldera.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Mount Rinjani has also been volcanically active, forming its own crater, Segara Muncar.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Other volcanoes in the region include Agung, Batur, and Bratan, on the island of Bali to the west.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Lombok is one of the Lesser Sunda Islands in the Sunda Arc of Indonesia, a subduction zone where the Indo-Australian Plate subducts beneath the Eurasian Plate at a rate of 7 centimetres per year (2.8 in/year).
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The magmas feeding Mount Samalas and Mount Rinjani are likely derived from peridotite rocks beneath Lombok, in the mantle wedge.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The oldest geological units on Lombok are from the Oligocene–Miocene, with old volcanic units cropping out in southern parts of the island.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Samalas was built up by volcanic activity before 12,000 BP.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Additional eruptions by either Rinjani or Samalas are dated 11,980 ± 40, 11,940 ± 40, and 6,250 ± 40 BP.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Eruptive activity continued until about 500 years before 1257.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Volcanic activity mostly consists of explosive eruptions and ash flows.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The rocks of the Samalas volcano are mostly dacitic, with a SiO 2 content of 62–63 percent by weight.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The rocks expelled during the 1257 eruption formed from aluminum-rich basalt through fractional crystallization and other physical processes.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Volcanic rocks in the Banda arc are mostly calc-alkaline ranging from basalt over andesite to dacite.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The crust beneath the volcano is about 20 kilometres (12 mi) thick, and the lower extremity of the Wadati–Benioff zone is about 164 kilometres (102 mi) deep.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The events of the 1257 eruption have been reconstructed through geological analysis of the deposits it left and by historical records.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption probably occurred during the northern summer in September (uncertainty of 2–3 months) that year, in light of the time it would have taken for its traces to reach the polar ice sheets and be recorded in ice cores and the pattern of tephra deposits.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] 1257 is the most likely year of the eruption, although a date of 1258 is also possible.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] It is possible that the accumulation of vapours in the magmatic system over the preceding centuries destabilized it, until the 1257 eruption commenced.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The phases of the eruption are also known as P1 (phreatic and magmatic phase), P2 (phreatomagmatic with pyroclastic flows), P3 (Plinian) and P4 (pyroclastic flows).
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] They produced rocks with similar composition, unlike other volcanoes where different stages often feature rocks with different compositions.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The duration of the P1 and P3 phases is not known individually, but the two phases combined (not including P2) lasted between 12 and 15 hours.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption column reached a height of 39–40 kilometres (24–25 mi) during the first stage (P1), and of 38–43 kilometres (24–27 mi) during the third stage (P3); it was high enough that SO2 in it and its sulfur isotope ratio was influenced by photolysis at high altitudes.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption began with a phreatic (steam explosion powered) stage that deposited 3 centimetres (1.2 in) of ash over 400 square kilometres (150 sq mi) of northwest Lombok.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] A magmatic stage followed, and lithic-rich pumice rained down, the fallout reaching a thickness of 8 centimetres (3.1 in) both upwind on East Lombok and on Bali.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] This was followed by lapilli rock as well as ash fallout, and pyroclastic flows that were partially confined within the valleys on Samalas's western flank.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Some ash deposits were eroded by the pyroclastic flows, which created furrow structures in the ash.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Pyroclastic flows crossed 10 kilometres (6.2 mi) of the Bali Sea, reaching the Gili Islands to the northwest of Samalas and Taliwang east of Lombok, while pumice blocks presumably covered the Alas Strait between Lombok and Sumbawa.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The deposits show evidence of interaction of the lava with water, so this eruption phase was probably phreatomagmatic.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] It was followed by three pumice fallout episodes, with deposits over an area wider than was reached by any of the other eruption phases.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] These pumices fell up to 61 kilometres (38 mi) to the east, against the prevailing wind, in Sumbawa, where they are up to 7 centimetres (2.8 in) thick.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The deposition of these pumices was followed by another stage of pyroclastic flow activity, probably caused by the collapse of the eruption column that generated the flows.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] At this time the eruption changed from an eruption-column-generating stage to a fountain-like stage and the caldera began to form.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] These pyroclastic flows were deflected by the topography of Lombok, filling valleys and moving around obstacles such as older volcanoes as they expanded across the island incinerating the island's vegetation.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Interaction between these flows and the air triggered the formation of additional eruption clouds and secondary pyroclastic flows.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Where the flows entered the sea north and east of Lombok, steam explosions created pumice cones on the beaches and additional secondary pyroclastic flows.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Pyroclastic flows descended the northern slopes of Samalas; on the southern slopes they split into two branches that proceeded to the Alas Strait to the east and the Bali Strait to the west.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Coral reefs were buried by the pyroclastic flows; some flows crossed the Alas Strait between Sumbawa and Lombok and formed deposits on Sumbawa.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] These pyroclastic flows reached volumes of 29 cubic kilometres (7.0 cu mi) on Lombok, and thicknesses of 35 metres (115 ft) as far as 25 kilometres (16 mi) from Samalas.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The pyroclastic flows altered the geography of Lombok; they and sediments eroded from the Samalas deposits extended the shorelines of the island and buried river valleys; a new river network developed on the volcanic deposits after the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Volcanic rocks ejected by the eruption covered Bali and Lombok and parts of Sumbawa.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Tephra in the form of layers of fine ash from the eruption fell as far away as Java, forming part of the Muntilan Tephra, which was found on the slopes of other volcanoes of Java, but could not be linked to eruptions in these volcanic systems.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] This tephra is now considered to be a product of the 1257 eruption and is thus also known as the Samalas Tephra.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] It reaches thicknesses of 2–3 centimetres (0.79–1.18 in) on Mount Merapi, 15 centimetres (5.9 in) on Mount Bromo, 22 centimetres (8.7 in) at Ijen and 12–17 centimetres (4.7–6.7 in) on Bali's Agung volcano.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In Lake Logung 340 kilometres (210 mi) away from Samalas on Java it is 3 centimetres (1.2 in) thick.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Most of the tephra was deposited west-southwest of Samalas.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Considering the thickness of Samalas Tephra found at Mount Merapi, the total volume may have reached 32–39 cubic kilometres (7.7–9.4 cu mi).
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Pumice falls with a fine graining and creamy colour from the Samalas eruption have been used as a tephrochronological marker on Bali.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Tephra from the volcano was found in Colombian sediments, and in ice cores as far as 13,500 kilometres (8,400 mi) away, and a tephra layer sampled at Dongdao island in the South China Sea has been tentatively linked to Samalas.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Ash and aerosols might have impacted humans and corals at large distances from the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] There are several estimates of the volumes expelled during the various stages of the Samalas eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The first stage reached a volume of 12.6–13.4 cubic kilometres (3.0–3.2 cu mi).
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The phreatomagmatic phase has been estimated to have had a volume of 0.9–3.5 cubic kilometres (0.22–0.84 cu mi).
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The total dense rock equivalent volume of the whole eruption was at least 40 cubic kilometres (9.6 cu mi).
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] On Lombok, it forms the Kalibabak Formation, a geological rock formation.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The magma erupted was trachydacitic and contained amphibole, apatite, clinopyroxene, iron sulfide, orthopyroxene, plagioclase, and titanomagnetite.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] It formed out of basaltic magma by fractional crystallization and had a temperature of about 1,000 °C (1,830 °F).
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Its eruption may have been triggered either by the entry of new magma into the magma chamber or the effects of gas bubble buoyancy.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption had a Volcanic Explosivity Index of 7, making it one of the largest eruptions of the current epoch, the Holocene.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Such large volcanic eruptions can result in catastrophic impacts on humans and widespread loss of life both close to the volcano and at greater distances.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption created the 6–7 kilometres (3.7–4.3 mi) wide Segara Anak caldera where the Samalas mountain was formerly located; within its 700–2,800 metres (2,300–9,200 ft) high walls, a 200 metres (660 ft) deep crater lake formed called Lake Segara Anak.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The Barujari cone rises 320 metres (1,050 ft) above the water of the lake and has erupted 15 times since 1847.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] A crater lake may have existed on Samalas before the eruption and supplied its phreatomagmatic phase with 0.1–0.3 cubic kilometres (0.024–0.072 cu mi) of water.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Alternatively, the water could have been supplied by aquifers.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Approximately 2.1–2.9 cubic kilometres (0.50–0.70 cu mi) of rock from Rinjani fell into the caldera, a collapse that was witnessed by humans and left a collapse structure that cuts into Rinjani's slopes facing the Samalas caldera.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption that formed the caldera was first recognized in 2003, and in 2004 a volume of 10 cubic kilometres (2.4 cu mi) was attributed to this eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Early research considered that the caldera-forming eruption occurred between 1210 and 1300.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In 2013, Lavigne suggested that the eruption occurred between May and October 1257, resulting in the climate changes of 1258.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Several villages on Lombok are constructed on the pyroclastic flow deposits from the 1257 event.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] A major volcanic event in 1257–1258 was first discovered from data in ice cores; specifically increased sulfate concentrations were found in 1980 within the Crête ice core (Greenland, drilled in 1974) associated with a deposit of rhyolitic ash.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption was known as the "mystery eruption".
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Sulfate spikes were also found in ice cores from Ellesmere Island, Canada, and the Samalas sulfate spikes were used as stratigraphic markers for ice cores even before the volcano that caused them was known.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The ice cores indicated a large sulfate spike, accompanied by tephra deposition, around 1257–1259, the largest in 7,000 years and twice the size of the spike due to the 1815 eruption of Tambora.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In 2003, a dense rock equivalent volume of 200–800 cubic kilometres (48–192 cu mi) was estimated for this eruption, but it was also proposed that the eruption might have been somewhat smaller and richer in sulfur.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The volcano responsible was thought to be located in the Ring of Fire but could not be identified at first; Tofua volcano in Tonga was proposed at first but dismissed, as the Tofua eruption was too small to generate the 1257 sulfate spikes.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] A volcanic eruption in 1256 at Harrat al-Rahat near Medina was also too small to trigger these events.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Other proposals included several simultaneous eruptions.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The diameter of the caldera left by the eruption was estimated to be 10–30 kilometres (6.2–18.6 mi), and the location was estimated to be close to the equator and probably north of it.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] While at first no clear-cut climate anomaly could be correlated to the 1257 sulfate layers, in 2000 climate phenomena were identified in medieval records of the northern hemisphere that are characteristic for volcanic eruptions.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Earlier, climate alterations had been reported from studies of tree rings and climate reconstructions.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The deposits showed that climate disturbances reported at that time were due to a volcanic event, the global spread indicating a tropical volcano as the cause.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The suggestion that Samalas/Rinjani might be the source volcano was first raised in 2012, since the other candidate volcanoes—El Chichón and Quilotoa—did not match the chemistry of the sulfur spikes.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] El Chichon, Quilotoa and Okataina were also inconsistent with the timespan and size of the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The conclusive link between these events and an eruption of Samalas was made in 2013 on the basis of radiocarbon dating of trees on Lombok and the *Babad Lombok*, a series of writings in Old Javanese on palm leaves that described a catastrophic volcanic event on Lombok which occurred before 1300.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] These findings induced Franck Lavigne, a geoscientist of the Pantheon-Sorbonne University who had already suspected that a volcano on that island may be responsible, to conclude that the Samalas volcano was this volcano.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The role of the Samalas eruption in the global climate events was confirmed by comparing the geochemistry of glass shards found in ice cores to that of the eruption deposits on Lombok.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Later, geochemical similarities between tephra found in polar ice cores and eruption products of Samalas reinforced this localization.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Ice cores in the northern and southern hemisphere display sulfate spikes associated with Samalas.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The signal is the strongest in the southern hemisphere over the last 1000 years; one reconstruction even considers it the strongest of the last 2500 years.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] It is about eight times stronger than that of Krakatau.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In the northern hemisphere it is only exceeded by the signal of the destructive 1783/1784 Laki eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The ice core sulfate spikes have been used as a time marker in chronostratigraphic studies.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Ice cores from Illimani in Bolivia contain thallium and sulfate spikes from the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] For comparison, the 1991 eruption of Pinatubo ejected only about a tenth of the amount of sulfur erupted by Samalas.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Sulfate deposition from the Samalas eruption has been noted at Svalbard, and the fallout of sulfuric acid from the volcano may have directly affected peatlands in northern Sweden.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In addition, the sulfate aerosols may have extracted large amounts of the beryllium isotope 10 Be from the stratosphere; such an extraction event and the subsequent deposition in ice cores may mimic changes in solar activity.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The amount of sulfur dioxide released by the eruption has been estimated to be 158 ± 12 million tonnes.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Whether the mass release was higher or lower than for Tambora is contentious; Tambora might have produced more or less sulfur than Samalas, or Samalas may have been more effective at injecting tephra into the stratosphere.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] After the eruption, it probably took weeks to months for the fallout to reach large distances from the volcano.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] When large scale volcanic eruptions inject aerosols into the atmosphere, they can form stratospheric veils.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] These reduce the amount of light reaching the surface and cause lower temperatures, which can lead to poor crop yields.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Such sulfate aerosols in the case of the Samalas eruption may have remained at high concentrations for about three years according to findings in the Dome C ice core in Antarctica, although a smaller amount may have persisted for an additional time.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Cooling may have lasted for 4–5 years based on simulations and tree ring data.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Another effect of the eruption-induced climate change may have been a brief decrease in atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The Samalas signal is only inconsistently reported from tree ring climate information, and the temperature effects were likewise limited, probably because the large sulfate output altered the average size of particles and thus their radiative forcing.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Climate modelling indicated that the Samalas eruption may have reduced global temperatures by approximately 2 °C (3.6 °F), a value largely not replicated by proxy data.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Better modelling with a general circulation model that includes a detailed description of the aerosol indicated that the principal temperature anomaly occurred in 1258 and continued until 1261.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Climate models tend to overestimate the climate impact of a volcanic eruption; one explanation is that climate models tend to assume that aerosol optical depth increases linearly with the quantity of erupted sulfur when in reality self-limiting processes limit its growth.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The possible occurrence of an El Niño before the eruption may have further reduced the cooling, especially in Alaska.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The Samalas eruption, together with 14th century cooling, is thought to have set off a growth of ice caps and sea ice, and glaciers in the Alps, Bhutan Himalaya, the Pacific Northwest and the Patagonian Andes grew in size.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The advances of ice after the Samalas eruption may have strengthened and prolonged the climate effects.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Later volcanic activity in 1269, 1278, and 1286 and the effects of sea ice on the North Atlantic would have further contributed to ice expansion.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The glacier advances triggered by the Samalas eruption are documented on Baffin Island, where the advancing ice killed and then incorporated vegetation, conserving it.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Likewise, a change in Arctic Canada from a warm climate phase to a colder one coincides with the Samalas eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] According to 2003 reconstructions, summer cooling reached 0.69 °C (1.24 °F) in the southern hemisphere and 0.46 °C (0.83 °F) in the northern hemisphere.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] More recent proxy data indicate that a temperature drop of 0.7 °C (1.3 °F) occurred in 1258 and of 1.2 °C (2.2 °F) in 1259, but with differences between various geographical areas.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] For comparison, the radiative forcing of Pinatubo's 1991 eruption was about a seventh of that of the Samalas eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Sea surface temperatures too decreased by 0.3–2.2 °C (0.54–3.96 °F), triggering changes in the ocean circulations.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Ocean temperature and salinity changes may have lasted for a decade.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Precipitation and evaporation both decreased, evaporation reduced more than precipitation.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Volcanic eruptions can also deliver bromine and chlorine into the stratosphere, where they contribute to the breakdown of ozone through their oxides chlorine monoxide and bromine monoxide.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] One hypothesis is that the resulting increase in ultraviolet radiation on the surface of Earth may have led to widespread immunosuppression in human populations, explaining the onset of epidemics in the years following the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Samalas, along with the 1452/1453 mystery eruption and the 1815 eruption of Mount Tambora, was one of the strongest cooling events in the last millennium, even more so than at the peak of the Little Ice Age.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] After an early warm winter 1257–1258 resulting in the early flowering of violets according to reports from the Kingdom of France, European summers were colder after the eruption, and winters were long and cold.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The Samalas eruption came after the Medieval Climate Anomaly, a period early in the last millennium with unusually warm temperatures, and at a time when a period of climate stability was ending, with earlier eruptions in 1108, 1171, and 1230 already having upset global climate.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Subsequent time periods displayed increased volcanic activity until the early 20th century.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The time period 1250–1300 was heavily disturbed by volcanic activity from four eruptions in 1230, 1257, 1276 and 1286, and is recorded by a moraine from a glacial advance on Disko Island, although the moraine may indicate a pre-Samalas cold spell.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] These volcanic disturbances along with positive feedback effects from increased ice may have started the Little Ice Age even without the need for changes in solar radiation, though this theory is not without disagreement.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The Samalas eruption in Europe is sometimes used as a chronological marker for the beginning of the Little Ice Age.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Other regions such as Alaska were mostly unaffected.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] There is little evidence that tree growth was influenced by cold in what is now the Western United States, where the eruption may have interrupted a prolonged drought period.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The climate effect in Alaska may have been moderated by the nearby ocean.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In 1259, Western Europe and the west coastal North America had mild weather and there is no evidence for summer precipitation changes in Central Europe.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Tree rings do not show much evidence of precipitation changes.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption led to global disaster in 1257–1258.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Very large volcanic eruptions can cause significant human hardship, including famine, away from the volcano due to their effect on climate.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The social effects are often reduced by the resilience of humans; thus there is often uncertainty about causal links between volcano-induced climate variations and societal changes at the same time.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Western and central Indonesia at the time were divided into competing kingdoms that often built temple complexes with inscriptions documenting historical events.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] However, little direct historical evidence of the consequences of the Samalas eruption exists.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The *Babad Lombok* describe how villages on Lombok were destroyed during the mid-13th century by ash, gas and lava flows, and two additional documents known as the *Babad Sembalun* and *Babad Suwung* may also reference the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] They are also—together with other texts—the source of the name "Samalas" while the name "Suwung"—"quiet and without life"—may, in turn, be a reference to the aftermath of the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The city of Pamatan, capital of a kingdom on Lombok, was destroyed, and both disappeared from the historical record.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The royal family survived the disaster according to the Javanese text, which also mentions successful reconstruction and recovery efforts after the eruption, and there is no clear-cut evidence that the kingdom itself was destroyed by the eruption, as the history there is poorly known in general.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Thousands of people died, although it is possible that the population of Lombok fled before the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In Bali the number of inscriptions dropped off after the eruption, and Bali and Lombok may have been depopulated by it, possibly for generations, allowing King Kertanegara of Singhasari on Java to conquer Bali in 1284 with little resistance.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] It might have taken about a century for Lombok to recover from the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The *Babad Suwung* reports destruction on the western coast of Sumbawa, which was depopulated and remains so to this day; presumably the local populace viewed the area devastated by the eruption as "forbidden" and this memory persisted until recent times.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Around 1300, settlements in many places of the Pacific relocated, perhaps because of a sea level drop that occurred after 1250, and the 1991 eruption of Pinatubo has been linked to small drops in sea level.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Climate change triggered by the Samalas eruption and the beginning of the Little Ice Age may have led to people in Polynesia migrating southwestward in the 13th century.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The first settlement of New Zealand most likely occurred 1230–1280 AD and the arrival of people there and on other islands in the region may reflect such a climate-induced migration.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] However, the climate history of the Southern Hemisphere is poorly known, and thus linking Samalas to specific events impossible.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Contemporary chronicles in Europe mention unusual weather conditions in 1258.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Reports from 1258 in France and England indicate a dry fog, giving the impression of a persistent cloud cover to contemporary observers.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Medieval chronicles say that in 1258, the summer was cold and rainy, causing floods and bad harvests, with cold from February to June.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Frost and snow fell during summer 1259 in Russia, according to chronicles.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In Europe and the Middle East, changes in atmospheric colours, storms, cold, and severe weather were reported in 1258–1259, with agricultural problems extending to North Africa.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In Europe, excess rain, cold and high cloudiness damaged crops and caused famines followed by epidemics, although 1258–1259 did not lead to famines as bad as some other famines such as the Great Famine of 1315–17.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The price for cereal increased in Britain, France, and Italy, augmented by price speculation.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Outbreaks of disease occurred during this time in the Middle East, England and Italy, including typhus.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] During and after the winter of 1258–59, exceptional weather was reported less commonly, but the winter of 1260–61 was very severe in Iceland, Italy, and elsewhere.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The disruption caused by the eruption may have influenced the onset of the Mudéjar revolt of 1264–1266 in Iberia.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] A famine in London has been linked to this event; this food crisis was not extraordinary and there were issues with harvests already before the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The famine occurred at a time of political crisis between King Henry III of England and the English magnates.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Witnesses reported a death toll of 15,000 to 20,000 in London.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] A mass burial of famine victims was found in the 1990s in the centre of London.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Matthew Paris of St Albans described how until mid-August 1258, the weather alternated between cold and strong rain, causing high mortality.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The resulting famine was severe enough that grain was imported from Germany and Holland.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In Italy, bad weather including intense rains in 1258 caused crop failures throughout the peninsula, as documented by numerous chronicles, although impacts varied between regions.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Relative to most of Europe, the impact in Italy hit a year later.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In 1259, a cold wave led to high mortality throughout Italy.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The cities of Bologna and Siena in Italy attempted to manage the food crisis by buying and subsidizing grain, banning its export and limiting its price.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Siena also initiated diplomatic relations with Manfred, King of Sicily, ostensibly to help manage the food crisis, while a political crisis arose in Bologna, which was also weakened geopolitically.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Parma ordered the sale of grain and tasked officials with monitoring markets, including closing them on Saturdays, and banned food exports.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] It is likely that the overthrow of the podestá (lord) of Parma Giberto da Gente in 1259 was facilitated by the crisis, which induced his supporters to remain passive.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In Pavia, where a political crisis was already underway in 1257, various economical and police measures were taken during the following two years to secure food supplies.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The city of Como in northern Italy repaired river banks that had been damaged by flooding, and acquired grain for its consumption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In Perugia, there were three years of food crisis between 1257 and 1260, and the question of food supply played a major role in city politics and drove increased social control.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Perugia is also where the Flagellant movement arose; it may have originated in the social distress caused by the effects of the eruption, though warfare and other causes probably played a more important role than natural events.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Over the long term, the cooling of the North Atlantic and sea ice expansion therein may have impacted the societies of Greenland and Iceland by restraining navigation and agriculture, perhaps allowing further climate shocks around 1425 to end the existence of the Norse settlement in Greenland.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Another possible longer-term consequence of the eruption was the Byzantine Empire's loss of control over western Anatolia, because of a shift in political power from Byzantine farmers to mostly Turkoman pastoralists in the area.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Colder winters caused by the eruption would have impacted agriculture more severely than pastoralism.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The 1257 Samalas eruption took place during the Pueblo III Period in southwestern North America, during which the Mesa Verde region on the San Juan River was the site of the so-called cliff dwellings.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Several sites were abandoned after the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption took place during a time of decreased precipitation and lower temperatures and when population was declining.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The Samalas eruption was one among several eruptions during this period which may have triggered climate stresses such as a colder climate, which in turn caused strife within the society of the Ancestral Puebloans; possibly they left the northern Colorado Plateau as a consequence.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In the Altiplano of South America, a cold and dry interval between 1200 and 1450 has been associated with the Samalas eruption and the 1280 eruption of Quilotoa volcano in Ecuador.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The use of rain-fed agriculture increased in the area between the Salar de Uyuni and the Salar de Coipasa despite the climatic change, implying that the local population effectively coped with the effects of the eruption.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Problems were also recorded in China, Japan, and Korea.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] In Japan, the *Azuma Kagami* chronicle mentions that rice paddies and gardens were destroyed by the cold and wet weather, and the so-called Shōga famine – which among other things stimulated the Japanese religious reformer Nichiren – may have been aggravated by bad weather in 1258 and 1259.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Along with the Mongol invasions of Korea, hardship caused by the Samalas eruption may have precipitated the downfall of the Goryeo military regime and of its last Choe dictator, Ch'oe Ui.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Monsoon anomalies triggered by the Samalas eruption may have also impacted Angkor Wat in present-day Cambodia, which suffered a population decline at that time.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The effects of the eruption, such as famines, droughts and epidemics may also have hastened the decline of the Mongol Empire, although the volcanic event is unlikely to have been the sole cause.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] It may have altered the outcome of the Toluid Civil War and shifted its centre of power towards the Chinese part dominated by Kublai Khan which was more adapted to cold winter conditions.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] The eruption of Samalas and other volcanoes caused climate disturbances in Central Asia, including a cooling which was followed by a warming.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] This warming may have provided the environmental conditions for the spread of *Yersinia pestis*, the causative agent of the plague, although its diversification in the Tian Shan had begun earlier in the 13th century.
[src:explosion/1257-samalas-eruption] Human populations may have been weakened by volcanic cooling-induced food crises and political/military unrest, facilitating the establishment of the outbreak.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] In April 1815, Mount Tambora, a volcano on the island of Sumbawa in present-day Indonesia (then part of the Dutch East Indies), erupted in what is now considered the most powerful volcanic eruption in recorded human history.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] This eruption, with a volcanic explosivity index (VEI) of 7, ejected 37–45 km3 (8.9–10.8 cubic miles) of dense-rock equivalent (DRE) material into the atmosphere, and was the most recent confirmed VEI-7 eruption.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Although the Mount Tambora eruption reached a violent climax on 10 April 1815, increased steaming and small phreatic eruptions occurred during the next six months to three years.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The ash from the eruption column dispersed around the world and lowered global temperatures in an event sometimes known as the Year Without a Summer in 1816.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] This brief period of significant climate change triggered extreme weather and harvest failures in many areas around the world.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Several climate forcings coincided and interacted in a systematic manner that has not been observed after any other large volcanic eruption since the early Stone Age.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Mount Tambora experienced several centuries of dormancy before 1815, caused by the gradual cooling of hydrous magma in its closed magma chamber.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Inside the chamber at depths between 1.5 and 4.5 km (5,000 and 15,000 ft), the exsolution of a high-pressure fluid magma formed during cooling and crystallisation of the magma.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] In 1812, the volcano began to rumble and generated a dark cloud.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] On 5 April 1815, a giant eruption occurred, followed by thunderous detonation sounds heard in Makassar on Sulawesi 380 km (240 mi) away, Batavia (now Jakarta) on Java 1,260 km (780 mi) away, and Ternate on the Molucca Islands 1,400 km (870 mi) away.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] On the morning of 6 April, volcanic ash began to fall in East Java with faint detonation sounds lasting until 10 April.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] What was first thought to be the sound of firing guns was heard on 10 April in Trumon, Sumatra, more than 2,600 km (1,600 mi) away.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] New analysis and agreements in dates suggest the rumbles of Tambora were heard even farther in Nong Khai (modern-day Thailand) at 3,352 km (2,083 mi) away, Vientiane (modern-day Laos) at 3,368 km (2,093 mi) away, and perhaps Mukdahan (Thailand) at 3,117 km (1,937 mi) away.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] At about 7:00 p.m. on 10 April, the eruptions intensified.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The whole mountain was turned into a flowing mass of "liquid fire".
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Pumice stones of up to 20 cm (8 in) in diameter started to rain down around 8:00 p.m., followed by ash at around 9:00–10:00 p.m.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Soon after, a violent whirlwind ensued, which hit the village of Saugur (now Sangar), blowing down nearly every house and carrying everything it encountered into the air, including large trees.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Pyroclastic flows cascaded down the mountain to the sea on all sides of the peninsula, wiping out the village of Tambora, and affecting a total area on land of about 874 km2 (337 sq mi).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] A moderate-sized tsunami struck the shores of various islands in the Indonesian archipelago on April 10th, with a height of up to 4 m (13 ft) in Sanggar around 10:00 p.m.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] A tsunami of 1–2 m (3–7 ft) in height was reported in Besuki, East Java, before midnight, and one of 2 m (7 ft) in height in the Molucca Islands.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The total of tsunami related deaths has been estimated to be around 4,600.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Loud explosions were heard until the next evening, 11 April.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The ash veil spread as far as West Java and South Sulawesi.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] A nitrous odor was noticeable in Batavia, and heavy tephra-tinged rain fell, finally receding between 11 and 17 April.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The explosion had an estimated VEI of 7.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] An estimated 41 km3 (10 cu mi) of pyroclastic trachyandesite were ejected, weighing about 10 billion tonnes.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The density of fallen ash in Makassar was 636 kg/m3 (39.7 lb/cu ft).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Before the explosion, Mount Tambora's peak elevation was about 4,300 m (14,100 ft), making it one of the tallest peaks in the Indonesian archipelago.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The explosion dropped its peak height by about one-third, to only 2,851 m (9,354 ft).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The 1815 Tambora eruption is the largest observed eruption in recorded history, as shown in the table below.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The explosion was heard at least 2,600 km (1,600 mi) away and possibly over 3,350 km (2,080 mi) away, and ash fell at least 1,300 km (810 mi) away.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] All vegetation on the island was destroyed.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Uprooted trees, mixed with pumice ash, washed into the sea and formed rafts up to 5 km (3 mi) across.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Between 1 and 3 October, the British ships *Fairlie* and *James Sibbald* encountered extensive pumice rafts about 3,600 km (2,200 mi) west of Tambora.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Clouds of thick ash still covered the summit on 23 April.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Explosions ceased on 15 July, although smoke emissions were observed as late as 23 August.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Activity resumed in August 1819—a small eruption with "flames" and rumbling aftershocks, and was considered to be part of the 1815 eruption.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] This eruption was recorded at 2 on the VEI scale.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The eruption column reached the stratosphere at an altitude of more than 43 km (43,000 m).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The coarser ash particles settled out one to two weeks after the eruptions, but the finer ash particles stayed in the atmosphere from a few months to a few years at altitudes of 10–30 km (33,000–98,000 ft).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Longitudinal winds spread these fine particles around the globe, creating optical phenomena.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Prolonged and brilliantly colored sunsets and twilights were seen frequently in London between 28 June and 2 July 1815, and 3 September and 7 October 1815.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The glow of the twilight sky typically appeared orange or red near the horizon and purple or pink above.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The estimated number of deaths varies depending on the source.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Zollinger (1855) puts the number of direct deaths at 10,000, probably caused by pyroclastic flows.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] On Sumbawa, 18,000 starved to death or died of disease.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] About 10,000 people on Lombok died from disease and hunger.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Petroeschevsky (1949) estimated that about 48,000 people were killed on Sumbawa and 44,000 on Lombok.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Stothers in 1984 and several other authors have accepted Petroeschevsky's claim of 88,000 deaths in total.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] However, a 1998 journal article authored by J.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Tanguy and others claimed that Petroeschevsky's figures were unfounded and based on untraceable references.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Tanguy's revision of the death toll was based on Zollinger's work on Sumbawa for several months after the eruption and on Thomas Raffles's notes.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Tanguy pointed out that there may have been additional victims on Bali and East Java because of famine and disease.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Their estimate was 11,000 deaths from direct volcanic effects and 49,000 by post-eruption famine and epidemic diseases.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] According to Clive Oppenheimer, there were at least 71,000 deaths in total.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Reid has estimated that 100,000 people on Sumbawa, Bali and other locations died from the direct and indirect effects of the eruption.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] During the Northern Hemisphere summer of 1816, global temperatures cooled by 0.53 °C (0.95 °F).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] This cooling directly or indirectly caused 90,000 deaths.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The eruption of Mount Tambora was the largest cause of this climate anomaly.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] While there were other eruptions in 1815, Tambora is classified as a VEI-7 eruption with a column 45 km (148,000 ft) tall, eclipsing all others by at least one order of magnitude.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The VEI is used to quantify the amount of ejected material, with a VEI-7 being 100 km3 (24 cu mi).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Every index value below that is one order of magnitude (meaning ten times) less.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Furthermore, the 1815 eruption occurred during a Dalton Minimum, a period of unusually low solar radiation.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Volcanism plays a large role in climate shifts, both locally and globally.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] This was not always understood and did not enter scientific circles as fact until the 1883 eruption of Krakatoa tinted the skies orange.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The scale of the volcanic eruption will determine the significance of the impact on climate and other chemical processes, but a change will be measured even in the most local of environments.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] When volcanoes erupt, they eject carbon dioxide (CO2), water, hydrogen, sulfur dioxide (SO2), hydrogen chloride, hydrogen fluoride and many other gases (Meronen et al.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] CO2 and water are greenhouse gases, which comprise 0.0415 percent and 0.4 percent of the atmosphere, respectively.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Their small proportion disguises their significant role in trapping solar radiation and reradiating it back to Earth.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The 1815 eruption released SO2 into the stratosphere, causing a global climate anomaly.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Different methods have estimated the ejected sulfur mass during the eruption: the petrological method; an optical depth measurement based on anatomical observations; and the polar ice core sulfate concentration method, using cores from Greenland and Antarctica.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The figures vary depending on the method, ranging from 10 to 120 million tonnes.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] In the northern spring and summer of 1815, a persistent "dry fog" was observed in the northeastern United States.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The fog reddened and dimmed the sunlight, such that sunspots were visible to the naked eye.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Neither wind nor rainfall dispersed the "fog".
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] It was later identified as a stratospheric sulfate aerosol veil.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] In the summer of 1816, countries in the Northern Hemisphere suffered extreme weather conditions, dubbed the "Year Without a Summer".
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Average global temperatures decreased by about 0.4 to 0.7 °C (0.7 to 1.3 °F), enough to cause significant agricultural problems around the globe.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] On 4 June 1816, frosts were reported in the upper elevations of New Hampshire, Maine (then part of Massachusetts), Vermont and northern New York.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] On 6 June 1816, snow fell in Albany, New York, and Dennysville, Maine.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] On 8 June 1816, the snow cover in Cabot, Vermont, was reported still to be 46 cm (18 in) deep.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Such conditions occurred for at least three months and ruined most agricultural crops in North America.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Canada experienced extreme cold during that summer.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Snow 30 cm (12 in) deep accumulated near Quebec City from 6 to 10 June 1816.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The second-coldest year in the Northern Hemisphere since around 1400 was 1816, and the 1810s are the coldest decade on record.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] That was the consequence of Tambora's 1815 eruption and possibly another VEI-6 eruption in late 1808.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Parts of Europe also experienced a stormier winter.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] This climate anomaly has been blamed for the severity of typhus epidemics in southeast Europe and along the eastern Mediterranean Sea between 1816 and 1819.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The climate changes disrupted the Indian monsoons, caused three failed harvests and famine, and contributed to the spread of a new strain of cholera that originated in Bengal in 1816.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Many livestock died in New England during the winter of 1816–1817.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Cool temperatures and heavy rains resulted in failed harvests in the British Isles.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Families in Wales travelled long distances as refugees, begging for food.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Famine was prevalent in north and southwest Ireland, following the failure of wheat, oat and potato harvests.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The crisis was severe in Germany, where food prices rose sharply, and demonstrations in front of grain markets and bakeries, followed by riots, arson and looting, took place in many European cities.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] It was the worst famine of the 19th century.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Volcanism affects the atmosphere in two distinct ways: short-term cooling caused by reflected insolation and long-term warming from increased CO2 levels.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Most of the water vapor and CO2 is collected in clouds within a few weeks to months because both are already present in large quantities, so the effects are limited.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] It has been suggested that a volcanic eruption in 1809 may also have contributed to a reduction in global temperatures.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] By most calculations, the eruption of Tambora was at least a full order of magnitude (10 times) larger than that of Mount Pinatubo in 1991.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Its energy release was equivalent to about 33 gigatons of TNT (1.4×1020 J).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] An estimated 1,220 m (4,000 ft) of the top of the mountain collapsed to form a caldera, reducing the height of the summit by a third.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Around 100 km3 (24 cu mi) of rock was blasted into the air.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Toxic gases, including sulfur, were pumped into the atmosphere.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Volcanic ash was over 100 cm (40 in) deep within 75 km (45 mi) of the eruption, while areas within a 500 km (300 mi) radius saw a 5 cm (2 in) ash fall, and ash could be found as far away as 1,300 km (810 mi).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The ash burned and smothered crops, creating an immediate shortage of food in Indonesia.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The ejection of these gases, especially hydrogen chloride, caused the precipitation to be extremely acidic, killing much of the crops that survived or were rebudding during the spring.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The food shortages were compounded by the Napoleonic Wars, floods and cholera.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The ash in the atmosphere for several months after the eruption reflected significant amounts of solar radiation, causing unseasonably cool summers that contributed to food shortages.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] China, Europe and North America had well-documented below-normal temperatures, which devastated their harvests.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The monsoon season in China and India was altered, causing flooding in the Yangtze Valley and forcing thousands of Chinese to flee coastal areas.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The gases also reflected some of the already-decreased incoming solar radiation, causing a 0.4 to 0.7 °C (0.7 to 1.3 °F) decrease in global temperatures throughout the decade.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] An ice dam formed in Switzerland during the summers of 1816 and 1817.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The winter months of 1816 were not much different from previous years, but the spring and summer maintained the cool-to-freezing temperatures.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The winter of 1817, however, was radically different, with temperatures below −34 °C (−30 °F) in central and northern New York, which were cold enough to freeze lakes and rivers that were normally used to transport supplies.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Both Europe and North America suffered from freezes lasting well into June, with snow accumulating to 32 cm (13 in) in August, which killed recently planted crops and crippled the food industry.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The length of the growing seasons in parts of Massachusetts and New Hampshire were less than 80 days in 1816, resulting in harvest failures (Oppenheimer 2003).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Visually unique sunsets were observed in western Europe, and red fog was observed along the eastern coast of the U.S.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] These unique atmospheric conditions persisted for the better part of 2.5 years.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Scientists have used ice cores to monitor atmospheric gases during the cold decade (1810–1819), and the results have been puzzling.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The sulfate concentrations found in both Siple Station, Antarctica and central Greenland bounced from 5.0 in January 1816 to 1.1 in August 1818.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] This means that 25–30 megatons of sulfur were ejected into the atmosphere, most of which came from Tambora, followed by a rapid decrease through natural processes.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Tambora caused the largest shift in sulfur concentrations in ice cores for the past 5,000 years.Estimates of the sulfur yield vary from 10 megatons (Black et al.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] 2012) to 120 megatons (Stothers 2000), with the average of the estimates being 25–30 megatons.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The high concentrations of sulfur could have caused a four-year stratospheric warming of around 15 °C (27 °F), resulting in a delayed cooling of surface temperatures that lasted for nine years.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Climate data have shown that the variance between daily lows and highs may have played a role in the lower average temperature because the fluctuations were much more subdued.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Generally, the mornings were warmer because of nightly cloud cover and the evenings were cooler because the clouds had dissipated.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] There were documented fluctuations of cloud cover for various locations that suggested it was a nightly occurrence and the sun killed them off, much like a fog.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The class boundaries between 1810 and 1830 without volcanically perturbed years was around 7.9 °C (14.2 °F).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] In contrast, the volcanically perturbed years (1815–1817) had a change of only around 2.3 °C (4.1 °F).
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] This meant that the mean annual cycle in 1816 was more linear than bell shaped and 1817 endured cooling across the board.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Southeastern England, northern France and the Netherlands experienced the greatest amount of cooling in Europe, accompanied by New York, New Hampshire, Delaware and Rhode Island in North America.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] The documented rainfall was as much as 80 percent more than the calculated normal with regards to 1816, with unusually high amounts of snow in Switzerland, France, Germany and Poland.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] This is again contrasted by the unusually low precipitations in 1818, which caused droughts throughout most of Europe and Asia.(Auchmann et al.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] 2012) Russia had already experienced unseasonably warm and dry summers since 1815 and this continued for the next three years.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] There are also documented reductions in ocean temperature near the Baltic Sea, the North Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] This seems to have been an indicator of shifted oceanic circulation patterns and possibly changed wind direction and speed.(Meronen et al.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] Taking into account the Dalton Minimum and the presence of famine and droughts predating the eruption, the Tambora eruption accelerated or exacerbated the extreme climate conditions of 1815.
[src:explosion/1815-eruption-of-mount-tambora] While other eruptions and other climatological events would have led to a global cooling of about 0.2 °C (0.4 °F), Tambora increased on that benchmark substantially.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Between 19 May and 21 October 1883, the volcanic island of Krakatoa (located in the Sunda Strait, then part of the Dutch East Indies—modern-day Indonesia) began erupting, lasting more than five months.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] On 27 August, the island had its most significant eruption, which destroyed over 70% of the island and its surrounding archipelago, the island collapsing into a caldera.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruption of 27 August had an estimated volcanic explosivity index of 6, and is one of the deadliest and most destructive volcanic events in recorded history; the third explosion of that day, that occurred at 10:02 a.m., remains the loudest-known sound in history.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The explosion was heard 3,110 kilometres (1,930 mi) away in Perth, Western Australia, and Rodrigues near Mauritius, 4,800 kilometres (3,000 mi) away.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The acoustic pressure wave circled the globe more than three times.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At least 36,417 deaths are attributed to the eruption and the tsunamis it created.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Significant additional effects were felt worldwide in the days and weeks after the volcano's eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Additional seismic activity was reported until February 1884, but any reports after October 1883 were dismissed by Rogier Verbeek's subsequent investigation into the eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In the years before the 1883 eruption, seismic activity around the Krakatau volcano was intense, with earthquakes felt as far away as the Australian Northern Territory, one of which, in 1880, damaged a lighthouse.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Strombolian activity began on 20 May 1883, and steam venting began to occur regularly from Perboewatan, the northernmost of the island's three cones.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Eruptions of ash reached an estimated altitude of 6 kilometres (20,000 ft), and explosions could be heard in Batavia (Jakarta) 160 km (100 mi) away, rattling windows and doors.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] An excursion party sent to the island on 26 May reported that the islands were covered with a fine white dust, with explosions coming from Perboewatan every five to ten minutes.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Although by this time the eruptions were calming down, some of the explosions were still very energetic, hurling pumice opposite the direction of the wind.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] A large crater approximately 900 metres (3,000 ft) in diameter formed, with a cavity from which issued plumes of steam.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruptions soon quietened after the initial violence.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Around 16 June, there were loud explosions and a thick black cloud covered the islands for five days.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruptions started gaining strength again on 19 June.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] On 24 June, a prevailing east wind cleared the cloud, and two ash columns could be seen issuing from Krakatau.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] It was also noticed that the summit cone of Perboewatan was gone, which an extensive report of a few years later attributes it to having been blown away.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The seat of the eruption is believed to have been a new vent or vents that formed on that day, between Perboewatan and Danan.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The violence of the ongoing eruptions caused tides in the vicinity to be unusually high, and ships at anchor had to be moored with chains.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Earthquakes were felt at Anyer, Banten, and ships began to report large pumice masses to the west in the Indian Ocean.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] A third vent, and later many more, appeared.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruptions continued throughout July, and their violence continued to increase until the explosions of 27 August.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In early August, a Dutch topographical engineer, Captain H.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Ferzenaar, investigated the Krakatau islands.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] He noted three major ash columns (the newer from Danan), which obscured the western part of the island, and steam plumes from at least eleven other vents, mostly between Danan and Rakata.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] When he landed, he noted an ash layer about 50 cm (1.6 ft) thick and the destruction of all vegetation, leaving only tree stumps.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] He advised against any further landings.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] By 25 August, the Krakatau eruptions intensified.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At about 1:00 p.m. on 26 August, the eruption entered its climactic phase.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] By 2:00 p.m., a black ash cloud could be seen 27 km (89,000 ft) high.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At this point, the eruption was almost continuous, and explosions could be heard every ten minutes.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] By 5:00 p.m., the explosions were audible all over Java.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Waves approximately a metre high, which may have been produced by steam explosions, began battering the coasts of Java and Sumatra at 5:30 p.m., and continued throughout the night.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Ships within 20 km (12 mi) of the volcano reported heavy ash fall, with pieces of hot pumice up to 10 cm (4 in) in diameter landing on their decks.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Between 7:00 and 8:00 p.m., a small tsunami hit the shores of Java and Sumatra, 40 km (25 mi) away.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] On 27 August, a series of eleven enormous explosions occurred, which marked the climax of the eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At 5:30 a.m., the first explosion was at Perboewatan, triggering a tsunami heading to Telok Betong, now known as Bandar Lampung.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At 6:44 a.m., Krakatau exploded again at Danan, with the resulting tsunami propagating eastward and westward.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The third and largest explosion, at 10:02 a.m.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] (some sources say 9:58 a.m.), was so powerful that it was heard 3,110 km (1,930 mi) away in Perth, Western Australia, and the Indian Ocean island of Rodrigues near Mauritius, 4,800 km (3,000 mi) away, where the blast was thought to have been cannon fire from a nearby ship.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The third explosion was the loudest sound that has ever been measured.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The loudness of the blast heard 160 km (100 mi) from the volcano has been calculated to have been 180 dBSPL (180 dB re 20 μPa, or 20 kPa).
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Although heard at very great distances, the sounds of the largest explosions were much less noticeable, or not heard at all in close proximity to the volcano.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The reasons for this are complex and still debated by volcanologists today but a possible explanation is that the sound waves may have been projected upwards to the stratosphere and reflected away from the area, in part by ash suspended in the air.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Although often directly linked in popular accounts, the explosions and the tsunamis were probably caused by distinct mechanisms.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The explosions may have emanated from huge pulses of gas-laden magma, whilst the waves followed later when the ejecta slumped back down into the surrounding sea.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The worst of the many tsunamis that resulted were estimated to have been over 30 m (100 ft) high in places.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] A large area of the Sunda Strait and places on the Sumatran coast were affected by pyroclastic flows from the volcano.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Verbeek and others believe that the final major Krakatau eruption was a lateral blast, or pyroclastic surge.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Material shot out of the volcano at 2,575 km/h (1,600 mph).
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The energy released from the explosion has been estimated to be equal to about 200 megatonnes of TNT (840 petajoules), roughly four times as powerful as the Tsar Bomba, the most powerful thermonuclear weapon ever detonated.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This makes it one of the most powerful explosions in recorded history.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At 10:41 a.m., a landslide tore off half of Rakata's cone, along with the remainder of the island to the north of Rakata.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] It is still debated whether this event caused the loudest of the explosions but, either way, the collapse of the island into the magma chamber heralded the end of the paroxysmal phase.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Some islands in the western Indian Ocean, approximately 4,800 kilometres (3,000 mi) away, still heard it at nearly the same level as a gun blast.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Due to the limitations of the speed of sound, it is likely that people on these far away islands did not hear Krakatau for nearly four hours after its eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The pressure wave generated by the colossal third explosion radiated out from Krakatau at 1,086 km/h (675 mph).
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruption is estimated to have reached 180 dBSPL (180 dB re 20 μPa, or 20 kPa), loud enough to be heard 5,000 kilometres (3,100 mi) away.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] At Batavia, the air waves burst windows and cracked walls.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The pressure wave was recorded on barographs worldwide.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Several barographs recorded the wave seven times over five days: four times with the wave travelling away from the volcano to its antipodal point and three times travelling back to the volcano.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Hence, the wave rounded the globe three and a half times.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Massive tsunamis struck the coastlines of the Sunda Strait, entirely submerging some islands.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Some 80 km (50 mi) away, the low-lying Thousand Islands were submerged under 2 metres (7 ft) of seawater, forcing people to climb trees.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The tsunamis produced by the third explosion were the largest, although the first two explosions did produce smaller tsunamis.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The town of Merak was destroyed by a tsunami that was 46 metres (151 ft) high.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The waves reached heights of up to 24 metres (79 ft) along the south coast of Sumatra and up to 42 metres (138 ft) along the west coast of Java.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The tsunamis washed the land clean of vegetation and destroyed human settlements.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The *Loudon*, which at the time was anchored near the village of Telok Betong, survived the waves.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Away from the coasts of the Sunda Strait, the waves reached a height of four metres (13 ft) on Southern Sumatra.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Ships as far away as South Africa rocked as tsunamis hit them, and the victims' bodies were found floating in the ocean for months after the event.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The tsunamis which accompanied the eruption were believed to have been caused by gigantic pyroclastic flows entering the sea; each of the four great explosions was accompanied by large pyroclastic flows resulting from the gravitational collapse of the eruption columns.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This caused several cubic kilometres of material to enter the sea, displacing an equal volume of seawater.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Smaller waves were recorded on tidal gauges as far away as the English Channel.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] These occurred too soon to be remnants of the initial tsunamis, which owing to a wavelength of less than 7 km (4 mi), failed to cause significant damage at large distance, and may have been caused by concussive air waves from the eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] These air waves circled the globe several times and were still detectable on barographs five days later.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] About 10% of the eruption fatalities were from pyroclastic flows.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The pyroclastic flows and surges produced by the third explosion moved faster than 100 km/h (62 mph) and travelled over the sea up to 80 km (50 mi) from the source, affecting an area constrained to a minimum of 4,000 km2 (1,500 sq mi).
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Pyroclastic deposits thought to be from the flows have been found on Southeast Sumatra, and northwest of the volcano on the islands of Sebesi, Sebuku and Lagoendi, while on Southwest Sumatra the flows burnt victims.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] They travelled 40 km (25 mi) across the Sunda Strait.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Once they hit Southern Sumatra, they incinerated entire villages and burned all vegetation.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Two thousand of the corpses in Southern Sumatra appear to have been scorched to death, presumably by the pyroclastic flows.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Besse*, around 65 km (40 mi) north-northeast and 80 km (50 mi) east-northeast of Krakatau, respectively, were hit by strong winds and tephra.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] They were farther away than the scorched victims of the hot flows in Sumatra, so the ships and crew survived.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The flows had moved across the water on a cushion of superheated steam.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] There are also indications of submarine pyroclastic flows reaching 15 km (9 mi) from the volcano.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] An estimated 20 cubic kilometres (4.8 cu mi) of tephra was deposited.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Ash was propelled to an estimated height of 80 km (260,000 ft).
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] It is estimated that as much as 18–21 km3 (4.3–5.0 cu mi) of ignimbrite were deposited over 1.1 million km2 (420,000 sq mi).
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Around noon on 27 August 1883, a rain of hot ash fell around Ketimbang (now Kalianda in Lampung Province) in Sumatra, known as 'The Burning Ashes of Ketimbang', killing approximately 1,000 people in Sumatra.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] On the regional scale the effects were limited to some land in Banten, approximately 80 km south, never being repopulated and reverting to jungle, which is now the Ujung Kulon National Park.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Huge fields of floating pumice were reported for months after the event.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] There are numerous reports of groups of human skeletal remains floating across the Indian Ocean on rafts of volcanic pumice and washing up on the east coast of Africa up to a year after the eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] An observation made two weeks after the eruption describes the state of the affected areas, where the village of Tjaringin once was.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The official reported death toll was 36,417.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] There were no survivors from the 3,000 people on the island of Sebesi.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In the aftermath of the eruption, it was found that Krakatoa had almost entirely disappeared, except for the southern third.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Much of the Rakata cone had been sheared away, leaving behind a 250-metre (820 ft) cliff.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Of the northern two-thirds of the island, only a rocky islet named Bootsmansrots ('Bosun's Rock'), a fragment of Danan, was left; Poolsche Hoed had disappeared.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The huge amount of material the volcano deposited drastically altered the ocean floor.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The huge amount of ignimbrite deposits largely filled the 30–40-metre-deep (100–130 ft) basin around the mountain.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The land masses of Verlaten and Lang islands were increased, as was the western part of the remnant of Rakata.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Much of this gained material quickly eroded, but volcanic ash remains a significant part of the geological composition of these islands.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Two nearby sandbanks (called Steers and Calmeyer after the two naval officers who investigated them) were built up into islands by ashfall, but the sea later washed them away.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Seawater on hot volcanic deposits on Steers and Calmeyer had caused steam to rise, which some mistook for a continued eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In the year following the eruption, average Northern Hemisphere summer temperatures fell by 0.4 °C (0.72 °F).
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The record rainfall that hit Southern California during the water year from July 1883 to June 1884—Los Angeles received 970 millimetres (38.18 in) and San Diego 660 millimetres (25.97 in)—has been attributed to the Krakatoa eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] There was no El Niño during that period as is usual when heavy rain occurs in Southern California, but many scientists doubt that there was a causal relationship.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The eruption injected a tremendous amount of sulfur dioxide (SO2) gas high into the stratosphere, which was subsequently transported by high-level winds all over the planet.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This led to a global increase in sulfuric acid (H2SO4) concentration in high-level cirrus clouds.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The resulting increase in cloud reflectivity (or albedo) reflected more incoming light from the sun than usual and cooled the entire planet until the sulfur fell to the ground as acid rain.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The 1883 Krakatoa eruption darkened the sky worldwide for years afterwards and produced spectacular sunsets worldwide for many months.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] British artist William Ascroft made thousands of colour sketches of the red sunsets halfway around the world from Krakatoa in the years after the eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The ash caused "such vivid red sunsets that fire engines were called out in New York, Poughkeepsie and New Haven to quench the apparent conflagration".
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This eruption also produced a Bishop's Ring around the sun by day, and a volcanic purple light at twilight.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In 2004, an astronomer proposed the idea that the red sky shown in Edvard Munch's 1893 painting *The Scream* is an accurate depiction of the sky over Norway after the eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Weather watchers of the time tracked and mapped the effects on the sky.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] They labelled the phenomenon the "equatorial smoke stream".
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This was the first identification of what is known today as the jet stream.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] For several years following the eruption, it was reported that the moon appeared to be blue and sometimes green.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This was because some ash clouds were filled with particles about 1 μm wide—the right size to strongly scatter red light while allowing other colours to pass.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] White moonbeams shining through the clouds emerged blue and sometimes green.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] People also saw lavender suns and, for the first time, recorded noctilucent clouds.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Although the violent phase of the 1883 eruption was over by the late afternoon of 27 August, after light returned by 29 August, reports continued for months that Krakatoa was still in eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Verbeek's committee's earliest duties were to determine if this was true and verify reports of other volcanoes erupting on Java and Sumatra.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] In general, these were found to be false.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Small eruptions, mostly of mud, continued into October 1883.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Verbeek discounted any claims of Krakatoa still erupting after mid-October due to steaming of hot material, landslides due to heavy monsoon rains that season, and "hallucinations due to electrical activity" seen from a distance.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] No signs of further activity were seen until 1913 when an eruption was reported.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] An investigation could find no evidence the volcano was awakening.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] It was determined that what had been mistaken for renewed activity had been a major landslide (possibly the one which formed the second arc to Rakata's cliff).
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Examinations after 1930 of bathymetric charts made in 1919 show evidence of a bulge indicative of magma near the surface at the site that became Anak Krakatoa.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] The fate of northern Krakatoa has been the subject of some dispute among geologists.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] It was initially proposed that the island had been blown apart by the force of the eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Most of the material deposited by the volcano is magmatic in origin, and the caldera formed by the eruption is not extensively filled with deposits from the 1883 eruption.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] This indicates that the island subsided into an empty magma chamber at the end of the eruption sequence rather than having been destroyed during the eruptions.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Based on the findings of contemporary investigators, the established hypotheses assume that part of the island subsided before the first explosions on the morning of 27 August.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] Geological evidence does not support the assumption that only subsidence before the explosion was the cause.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] For instance, the pumice and ignimbrite deposits are not of a kind consistent with a magma-seawater interaction.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] A numerical model for a Krakatoa hydrovolcanic explosion and the resulting tsunami was described by Mader & Gittings, in 2006.
[src:explosion/1883-eruption-of-krakatoa] A high wall of water is formed that is initially higher than 100 metres driven by the shocked water, basalt and air.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Some 80,000 people were made homeless and 71 firemen lost their lives in the aftermath.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The ship was carrying a mixed cargo of cotton bales, timber, oil, gold, and ammunition including around 1,400 tons of explosives with an additional 240 tons of torpedoes and weapons.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The SS *Fort Stikine* was a 7,142 gross register ton freighter built in 1942 in Prince Rupert, British Columbia, under a lend-lease agreement; the name *Stikine* was derived from the Stikine River in British Columbia.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Sailing from Birkenhead on 24 February, via Gibraltar, Port Said and Karachi, she arrived at Bombay on 12 April 1944.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Her cargo included 1,395 tons of explosives including 238 tons of sensitive "A" explosives, torpedoes, mines, shells, and munitions.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] She also carried Supermarine Spitfire fighter aircraft, raw cotton bales, barrels of oil, timber, scrap iron and approximately £890,000 of gold bullion in bars in 31 crates.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The 8,700 bales of cotton and lubricating oil were loaded at Karachi and the ship's captain, Alexander James Naismith, recorded his protest about such a "mixture" of cargo.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The transportation of cotton through the sea route was inevitable for the merchants, as transporting cotton by rail from Punjab and Sindh to Bombay was banned at that time.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] In the mid-afternoon around 14:00, the crew were alerted to a fire onboard burning somewhere in the No.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The crew, dockside fire teams and fireboats were unable to extinguish the conflagration, despite pumping over 900 tons of water into the ship, and nor were they able to find the source due to the dense smoke.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The water was boiling all over the ship, due to heat generated by the fire.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] At 15:50 the order to abandon ship was given, and 16 minutes later there was a great explosion, cutting the ship in two and breaking windows over 12 km (7.5 mi) away.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] This and a later second explosion were powerful enough to be recorded by seismographs at the Colaba Observatory in the city.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Sensors recorded that the earth trembled at Shimla, a city over 1,700 km away.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The shower of burning material set fire to neighbourhoods in the area.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Around 2 km2 (0.77 mi2) were set ablaze in an 800 m (870 yd) arc around the ship.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Eleven neighbouring vessels had been sunk or were sinking, and the emergency personnel at the site suffered heavy losses.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Attempts to fight the fire were dealt a further blow when the second explosion from the ship swept the area at 16:34.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Burning cotton bales fell from the sky on docked ships, the dock yard, and neighbourhoods outside the harbour.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The sound of explosions was heard as far as 80 km (50 mi) away.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Some of the most developed and economically important parts of Bombay were wiped out by the blast and resulting fire.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The Australian hospital ship AHS *Wanganella* had been moored 2 nautical miles (3.7 km) off Bombay when the explosion occurred.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] She was subsequently brought in to port, spending a week treating the wounded before resuming her voyage to Taranto, Italy.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The details of the explosions and losses were first reported to the outside world by the Japanese-controlled Radio Saigon, which gave a detailed report of the incident on 15 April 1944.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] British-Indian wartime censorship permitted news reporters to send the reports only in the second week of May 1944.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] *Time* magazine published the story as late as 22 May 1944 and still it was news to the outside world.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] A movie depicting the explosions and aftermath, made by Indian cinematographer Sudhish Ghatak, was confiscated by military officers, although parts of it were shown to the public as a newsreel at a later date.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The total number of lives lost in the explosion is estimated at more than 800, while some estimates put the figure at around 1,300.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] More than 500 civilians lost their lives, many of them residing in adjoining slum areas, but as it was wartime, information about the full extent of the damage was partially censored.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Nine imported Locomotives were in the process of being unloaded from the docks since April 11 with 30 railway employees being present for the unloading process.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] By the noon of April 14 seven locomotives were still left to be loaded onto the wagons.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] This was because the Port Trust accidentally delivered the wrong wagons due to which the unloading could not take place.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] An employee of the BB&CI Railway provided an eyewitness account in the Railway Magazine, where he described how he and others, while being busy lashing and securing the locomotives, were surprised by the sudden noise of the explosions, and the flames shooting upward.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] An 80-pound steel plate dropped near the crane, narrowly missing him, and his accomplice.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The crew then jumped onto an already crowded barge, that was quickly moved away from the docks to safety.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Wandrekar, a senior journalist at *The Bombay Chronicle* newspaper, stated in a report dated 20 April 1944 that *Mumbaikars* (transl.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Residents of Mumbai) are always known for their good heart which is why around five days after the incident massive relief activities were shifted to the suburbs owing to the neutralisation of South Mumbai from the damages caused.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Soon after the calamity people from the affected areas began pouring into the suburbs.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] About six thousand persons from the Mandvi area, mostly middle class, went to Ghatkopar.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The workers and others from Ghatkopar got the three schools opened for their accommodation and private households also provided accommodation to these unfortunate families.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] There was a rush of labourers from the dock areas who wanted to get out of Bombay on foot by the Agra Road.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Ghatkopar workers opened a kitchen for them at the Hindu Sabha Hall.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The kitchen served food for about a thousand persons twice daily.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The Ghatkopar kitchen was still running when Vile Parle's Irla residents started running a second centre for about 500 persons, where food and lodging were provided for the refugees.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] A third kitchen was opened at Khotwadi and Narli Agripada in Santacruz where about 300 people were being served.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] In Khar, arrangements had been made to give rations to about a hundred persons who had found accommodation in Kherwadiand Old Khar village.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Khar Danda, a fishing village, had made arrangements for about a hundred people's accommodation and food.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Many families on Salsette Island, also known as Mumbai suburb, opened their doors to the needy.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] As part of the salvage operation, sub-lieutenant Ken Jackson, RNVR was seconded to the Indian government to establish the pumping operation.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] He and chief petty officer Charles Brazier arrived in Bombay on 7 May 1944.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Over a period of three months, many ships were salvaged.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The de-watering operation took three months to complete, after which Jackson and Brazier returned to their base in Colombo.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Jackson remained in the Far East for another two years, conducting further salvage work.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] For their efforts with the pumping operation, both men were rewarded: Brazier was awarded the MBE, and Jackson received an accelerated promotion.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] An Australian minesweeper, HMAS *Gawler*, landed working parties on 21 June 1944, to assist in the restoration of the port.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] It took three days to bring the fire under control, and later, 8,000 men toiled for seven months to remove around 500,000 tons of debris and bring the docks back into action.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The inquiry into the explosion identified the cotton bales as probably being the seat of the fire.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Many families lost all their belongings and were left with just the clothes on their backs.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] It was estimated that about 6,000 firms were affected, and 50,000 people lost their jobs.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The government took full responsibility for the disaster, and monetary compensation was paid to citizens who made a claim for loss or damage to property.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] During periodic dredging operations to maintain the depth of the docking bays, many intact gold bars have been found, some as late as February 2011, and returned to the government.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] A live shell weighing 45 kg (100 lb) was also found in October 2011.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] The Mumbai Fire Brigade's headquarters at Byculla has a memorial to the fire fighters who died.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] National Fire Safety Week is observed across India from 14 to 21 April, in memory of the 66 firemen who died in this explosion.
[src:explosion/1944-bombay-explosion] Apart from *Fort Stikine*, the following vessels were sunk or severely damaged.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens in Skamania County, Washington experienced a catastrophic explosive eruption which had a volcanic explosivity index of 5.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] It was the first to occur in the contiguous United States since the much smaller 1915 eruption of Lassen Peak in California.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The main eruption was preceded by a series of volcanic explosions, pyroclastic flows, and phreatic blasts beginning in March 1980.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] It has often been considered the most disastrous volcanic event in U.S. history.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The eruption was preceded by a series of earthquakes and steam-venting episodes caused by an injection of magma at shallow depth below the volcano that created a large bulge and a fracture system on the mountain's north slope.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] An earthquake at 8:32:11 am PDT (UTC−7) on May 18, 1980, caused the entire weakened north face to slide away, a sector collapse which was the largest subaerial landslide in recorded history.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This allowed the partly molten rock, rich in high-pressure gas and steam, to suddenly explode northward toward Spirit Lake in a hot mix of lava and pulverized rock, overtaking the landslide.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] An eruption column rose 80,000 feet (24 km; 15 mi) into the atmosphere and deposited ash in 11 U.S. states and various Canadian provinces.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At the same time, snow, ice, and several entire glaciers on the volcano melted, forming a series of large lahars (volcanic mudslides) that reached as far as the Columbia River, nearly 50 miles (80 km; 260,000 ft) to the southwest.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Less severe outbursts continued into the next day, only to be followed by other large, but not as destructive, eruptions later that year.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The thermal energy released during the eruption was equal to 26 megatons of TNT.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] About 57 people were killed, including innkeeper and World War I veteran Harry R.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Truman, photographers Reid Blackburn and Robert Landsburg, and volcanologist David A.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Hundreds of square miles were reduced to wasteland, causing over $1 billion in damage (equivalent to $3.5 billion in 2024).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Thousands of animals were killed, and Mount St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens was left with a crater on its north side.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At the time of the eruption, the summit of the volcano was owned by the Burlington Northern Railroad, but the United States Forest Service acquired the land from the railroad after the eruption.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The area was later preserved in the Mount St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens National Volcanic Monument and the State of Washington recognized the month of May as "Volcano Awareness Month".
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens and within the region to discuss the eruption and safety concerns, and to commemorate lives lost during the disaster.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens remained dormant from its last period of activity in the 1840s and 1850s until March 1980.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Several small earthquakes, beginning on March 15, indicated that magma might have begun moving below the volcano.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] On March 20, at 3:45 pm Pacific Standard Time, a shallow 4.2-magnitude earthquake, centered below the volcano's north flank, signaled the volcano's return from 123 years of hibernation.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A gradually building earthquake swarm saturated area seismographs and started to climax at about noon on March 25, reaching peak levels in the next two days, including an earthquake registering 5.1 on the Richter scale among a total of 174 shocks of magnitude 2.6 or greater.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Shocks of magnitude 3.2 or greater occurred at a slightly increasing rate during April and May, with five earthquakes of magnitude 4 or above per day in early April, and eight per day the week before May 18.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Initially, no direct sign of eruption was seen, but small earthquake-induced avalanches of snow and ice were reported from aerial observations.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At 12:36 pm on March 27, phreatic eruptions (explosions of steam caused by magma suddenly heating groundwater) ejected and smashed rock from within the old summit crater, excavating a new crater 250 feet (75 m) wide, and sending an ash column about 7,000 feet (2.1 km) into the air.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By this date, a 16,000-foot-long (4.9 km) eastward-trending fracture system had also developed across the summit area.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This was followed by more earthquake swarms and a series of steam explosions that sent ash 10,000 to 11,000 feet (3,000 to 3,400 m) above their vent.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Most of this ash fell between 3 and 12 mi (5 and 19 km) from its vent, but some was carried 150 mi (240 km) south to Bend, Oregon, or 285 mi (460 km) east to Spokane, Washington.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A second, new crater and a blue flame were observed on March 29.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The flame was visibly emitted from both craters and was probably created by burning gases.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Static electricity generated from ash clouds rolling down the volcano sent out lightning bolts that were up to 2 mi (3 km) long.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Ninety-three separate outbursts were reported on March 30, and increasingly strong harmonic tremors were first detected on April 1, alarming geologists and prompting Governor Dixy Lee Ray to declare a state of emergency on April 3.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Governor Ray issued an executive order on April 30 creating a "red zone" around the volcano; anyone caught in this zone without a pass faced a $500 fine (equivalent to $2,000 in 2025) or six months in jail.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This precluded many cabin owners from visiting their property.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A USGS (United States Geological Survey) team determined in the last week of April that a 1.5 mi-diameter (2.4 km) section of St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' north face was displaced outward by at least 270 ft (82 m).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] For the rest of April and early May, this bulge grew by 5 to 6 ft (1.5 to 1.8 m) per day, and by mid-May, it extended more than 400 ft (120 m) north.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] As the bulge moved northward, the summit area behind it progressively sank, forming a complex, down-dropped block called a graben.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Geologists announced on April 30 that sliding of the bulge area was the greatest immediate danger and that such a landslide might spark an eruption.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] These changes in the volcano's shape were related to the overall deformation that increased the volume of the volcano by 0.03 mi3 (0.13 km3) by mid-May.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This volume increase presumably corresponded to the volume of magma that pushed into the volcano and deformed its surface.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Because the intruding magma remained below ground and was not directly visible, it was called a cryptodome, in contrast to a true lava dome exposed at the surface.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Volcanologist Barry Voight was contacted by Rocky Crandell, a USGS employee working in the Vancouver office near the mountain.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Crandell sought Voight's expertise in landslides, hoping Voight would opine on the growing bulge.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In his reporting to Crandell and his associates, Voight, who observed the mountain from April 11-19, said that the bulge could fail and collapse the volcano's entire north sector.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] He suggested they begin monitoring the rate of movement of the bulge, worried that the collapse could trigger an eruption.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] He also advised hiring a local surveyor to take measurements, offending several of the geologists.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Shortly after, Voight left the mountain and returned to teaching classes at Pennsylvania State University.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] On May 1, he sent his full report to the USGS, summarizing his predictions, predicting the failure of the bulge and the collapse of the mountain's north side followed by a violent eruption that would require an extensive evacuation zone.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] On May 7, eruptions similar to those in March and April resumed, and over the following days, the bulge approached its maximum size.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] All activity had been confined to the 350-year-old summit dome and did not involve any new magma.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] About 10,000 earthquakes were recorded before the May 18 event, with most concentrated in a small zone less than 1.6 mi (2.6 km) directly below the bulge.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Visible eruptions ceased on May 16, reducing public interest and consequently the number of spectators in the area.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Mounting public pressure then forced officials to allow 50 carloads of property owners to enter the danger zone on Saturday, May 17, to gather whatever property they could carry.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Another trip was scheduled for 10 am the next day, a Sunday, when more than three hundred loggers who would normally be working in the area were not present.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By the time of the climactic eruption, dacite magma intruding into the volcano had forced the north flank outward nearly 500 ft (150 m) and heated the volcano's groundwater system, causing many steam-driven explosions (phreatic eruptions).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' activity did not show any change from the pattern of the preceding month.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The rates of bulge movement and sulfur dioxide emission, and ground temperature readings did not reveal any changes indicating a catastrophic eruption.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Johnston was on duty at an observation post around 6 mi (10 km) north of the volcano.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At 6:00 am Johnston's measurements did not indicate any unusual activity.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At 8:32 am, a magnitude 5.1 earthquake centered directly below the north slope triggered that part of the volcano to slide, approximately 7–20 seconds after the shock, followed a few seconds later by the main volcanic blast.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The sector collapse, the largest subaerial landslide in recorded history, traveled at 110 to 155 mph (180 to 250 km/h; 50 to 70 m/s) and moved across Spirit Lake's west arm.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Part of it hit a 1,150 ft-high (350 m) ridge about 6 mi (10 km) north.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Some of the slide spilled over the ridge, but most of it moved 13 mi (21 km) down the North Fork Toutle River, filling its valley up to 600 feet (180 m) deep with avalanche debris.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] An area of about 24 mi2 (62 km2) was covered, and the total volume of the deposit was about 0.7 mi3 (2.9 km3).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Rosenquist, his party, and his photographs survived because the blast was deflected by local topography 1 mi (1.6 km) short of his location.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' former north side became a rubble deposit 17 mi (27 km) long, averaging 150 ft (46 m) thick; the slide was thickest at 1 mi (1.6 km) below Spirit Lake and thinnest at its western margin.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The landslide temporarily displaced the waters of Spirit Lake to the ridge north of the lake, in a giant wave about 600 ft (180 m) high.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This, in turn, created a 295 ft (90 m) avalanche of debris consisting of the returning waters and thousands of uprooted trees and stumps.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Some of these remained intact with roots, but most had been sheared off at the stump seconds earlier by the blast of superheated volcanic gas and ash that had immediately followed and overtaken the initial landslide.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The debris was transported along with the water as it returned to its basin, raising the surface level of Spirit Lake by about 200 ft (61 m).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Four decades after the eruption, floating log mats persist on Spirit Lake and nearby St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens Lake, changing position with the wind.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The rest of the trees, especially those that were not completely detached from their roots, were turned upright by their own weight and became waterlogged, sinking into the muddy sediments at the bottom where they are in the process of becoming petrified in the anaerobic and mineral-rich waters.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This provides insight into other sites with a similar fossil record.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The landslide exposed the dacite magma in Mount St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' neck to much lower pressure, causing the gas-charged, partially molten rock and high-pressure steam above it to explode a few seconds after the landslide started.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Explosions burst through the trailing part of the landslide, blasting rock debris northward.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The resulting blast directed the pyroclastic flow laterally.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] It consisted of very hot volcanic gases, ash, and pumice formed from new lava, as well as pulverized old rock, which hugged the ground.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Initially moving about 220 mph (350 km/h), the blast quickly accelerated to around 670 mph (1,080 km/h), and it may have briefly passed the speed of sound.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Pyroclastic flow material passed over the moving avalanche and spread outward, devastating a fan-shaped area 23 miles across by 19 miles long (37 km by 31 km).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In total, about 230 sq mi (600 km2) of forest were knocked down, and extreme heat killed trees miles beyond the blow-down zone.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At its vent, the lateral blast probably did not last longer than about thirty seconds, but the northward-radiating and expanding blast cloud continued for about another minute.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This so-called "quiet zone" extended radially a few tens of miles from the volcano and was created by the complex response of the eruption's sound waves to differences in temperature and air motion of the atmospheric layers, and to a lesser extent, local topography.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Later studies indicated that one-third of the 0.045 mi3 (0.19 km3) of material in the flow was new lava, and the rest was fragmented, older rock.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The huge ensuing ash cloud sent skyward from St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' northern foot was visible throughout the quiet zone.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The near-supersonic lateral blast, loaded with volcanic debris, caused devastation as far as 19 mi (31 km) from the volcano.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Channelized blast zone, an intermediate zone, extended out to distances as far as 19 mi (31 km) from the volcano, an area in which the flow flattened everything in its path and was channeled to some extent by topography.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In this zone, the forces and direction of the blast are strikingly demonstrated by the parallel alignment of toppled large trees, broken off at the base of the trunk as if they were blades of grass mown by a scythe.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This zone was also known as the "tree-down zone".
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Channeling and deflection of the blast caused strikingly varied local effects that still remained conspicuous after some decades.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Where the blast struck open land directly, it scoured it, breaking trees off short and stripping vegetation and even topsoil, thereby delaying revegetation for many years.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Where the blast was deflected so as to pass overhead by several metres, it left the topsoil and the seeds it contained, permitting faster revegetation with scrub and herbaceous plants, and later with saplings.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Trees in the path of such higher-level blasts were broken off wholesale at various heights, whereas nearby stands in more sheltered positions recovered comparatively rapidly without conspicuous long-term harm.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Seared zone, also called the "standing dead" zone, the outermost fringe of the impacted area, is a zone in which trees remained standing, but were singed brown by the hot gases of the blast.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By the time this pyroclastic flow hit its first human victims, it was still as hot as 680 °F (360 °C) and filled with suffocating gas and flying debris.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Most of the 57 people known to have died in that day's eruption succumbed to asphyxiation, while several died from burns.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] He was able to protect his film with his body, and the surviving photos provided geologists with valuable documentation of the historic eruption.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Another eruption victim, amateur radio operator Gerry Martin, located near the Coldwater peak and farther north of Johnston's position 46°17′59.7″N 122°12′55″W﻿ / ﻿46.299917°N 122.21528°W﻿ / 46.299917; -122.21528, reported his sighting of the eruption enveloping the Coldwater II observation post.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] As the blast overwhelmed Johnston's post, Martin declared solemnly: "Gentlemen, the camper and car that's sitting over to the south of me is covered.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] It's going to hit me, too." before his radio went silent.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Subsequent outpourings of pyroclastic material from the breach left by the landslide consisted mainly of new magmatic debris rather than fragments of pre-existing volcanic rocks.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The resulting deposits formed a fan-like pattern of overlapping sheets, tongues, and lobes.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At least 17 separate pyroclastic flows occurred during the May 18 eruption, and their aggregate volume was about 0.05 mi3 (0.21 km3).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The flow deposits were still at about 570 to 790 °F (300 to 420 °C) two weeks after they erupted.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Secondary steam-blast eruptions fed by this heat created pits on the northern margin of the pyroclastic-flow deposits, at the south shore of Spirit Lake, and along the upper part of the North Fork Toutle River.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] These steam-blast explosions continued sporadically for weeks or months after the emplacement of pyroclastic flows, and at least one occurred a year later, on May 16, 1981.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] As the avalanche and initial pyroclastic flow were still advancing, a huge ash column grew to a height of 12 mi (19 km) above the expanding crater in less than ten minutes and spread tephra into the stratosphere for ten straight hours.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Near the volcano, the swirling ash particles in the atmosphere generated lightning, which in turn started many forest fires.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] During this time, parts of the mushroom-shaped ash-cloud column collapsed, and fell back upon the earth.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This fallout, mixed with magma, mud, and steam, sent additional pyroclastic flows speeding down St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Later, slower flows came directly from the new north-facing crater and consisted of glowing pumice bombs and very hot pumiceous ash.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Some of these hot flows covered ice or water, which flashed to steam, creating craters up to 65 ft (20 m) in diameter and sending ash as much as 6,500 ft (2,000 m) into the air.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Strong, high-altitude wind carried much of this material east-northeasterly from the volcano at an average speed around 60 miles per hour (100 km/h).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By 9:45 am, it had reached Yakima, Washington, 90 mi (140 km) away, and by 11:45 it was over Spokane, Washington.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A total of 4 to 5 in (100 to 130 mm) of ash fell on Yakima, and areas as far east as Spokane were plunged into darkness by noon, where visibility was reduced to 10 ft (3 m) and 0.5 in (13 mm) of ash fell.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' ash fell in the western part of Yellowstone National Park by 10:15 pm, and was seen on the ground in Denver the next day.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In time, ash fall from this eruption was reported as far away as Minnesota and Oklahoma, and some of the ash drifted around the globe within about two weeks.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] During the nine hours of vigorous eruptive activity, about 540,000,000 tons (540×10^6 short tons or 490×10^6 t) of ash fell over an area of more than 22,000 mi2 (57,000 km2).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The total volume of the ash before its compaction by rainfall was about 0.3 mi3 (1.3 km3).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The volume of the uncompacted ash is equivalent to about 0.05 mi3 (0.21 km3) of solid rock, or about 7% of the amount of material that slid off in the debris avalanche.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By 5:30 pm on May 18, the vertical ash column declined in stature, but less severe outbursts continued through the next several days.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Generally, given that the way airborne ash is deposited after an eruption is strongly influenced by the meteorological conditions, a certain variation of the ash type will occur, as a function of distance to the volcano or time elapsed from eruption.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens is no exception, hence the ash properties have large variations.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The bulk chemical composition of the ash has been found to be about 65% silicon dioxide, 18% aluminum oxide, 5% ferric oxide, 4% each calcium oxide and sodium oxide, and 2% magnesium oxide.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Trace elements were also detected, their concentrations varying as 0.05–0.09% chlorine, 0.02–0.03% fluorine, and 0.09–0.3% sulfur.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The index of refraction, a measure used in physics to describe how light propagates through a particular substance, is an important property of volcanic ash.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This number is *complex*, having both *real* and *imaginary* parts, the real part indicating how light disperses and the imaginary part indicating how light is absorbed by the substance.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The silicate particles are known to have a real index of refraction ranging between 1.5 and 1.6 for visible light.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] However, a spectrum of colors is associated with samples of volcanic ash, from very light to dark gray.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This makes for variations in the measured imaginary refractive index under visible light.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] For example, when comparing the imaginary part of the refractive index *k* of stratospheric ash from 9.3 and 11.2 mi (15 and 18 km) from the volcano, they have similar values around 700 nm (around 0.009), while they differ significantly around 300 nm.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Here, the 11.2 mi (18 km) sample (*k* was found to be around 0.009) was much more absorbent than the 9.3 mi (15 km) sample (*k* was found to be around 0.002).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The hot, exploding material also broke apart and melted nearly all of the mountain's glaciers, along with most of the overlying snow.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens eruptions, this created huge lahars (volcanic mudflows) and muddy floods that affected three of the four stream drainage systems on the mountain, and which started to move as early as 8:50 am.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Lahars travelled as fast as 90 mph (140 km/h) while still high on the volcano, but progressively slowed to about 3 mph (4.8 km/h) on the flatter and wider parts of rivers.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Mudflows from the southern and eastern flanks had the consistency of wet concrete as they raced down Muddy River, Pine Creek, and Smith Creek to their confluence at the Lewis River.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Bridges were taken out at the mouth of Pine Creek and the head of Swift Reservoir, which rose 2.6 ft (0.79 m) by noon to accommodate the nearly 18,000,000 yd3 (14,000,000 m3) of additional water, mud, and debris.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Glacier and snowmelt mixed with tephra on the volcano's northeast slope to create much larger lahars.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] These mudflows traveled down the north and south forks of the Toutle River and joined at the confluence of the Toutle forks and the Cowlitz River near Castle Rock, Washington, at 1:00 pm.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Ninety minutes after the eruption, the first mudflow had moved 27 mi (43 km) upstream, where observers at Weyerhaeuser's Camp Baker saw a 12 ft-high (4 m) wall of muddy water and debris pass.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Near the confluence of the Toutle's north and south forks at Silver Lake, a record flood stage of 23.5 ft (7.2 m) was recorded.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A large but slower-moving mudflow with a mortar-like consistency was mobilized in early afternoon at the head of the Toutle River north fork.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By 2:30 pm the massive mudflow had destroyed Camp Baker, and in the following hours, seven bridges were carried away.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Part of the flow backed up for 2.5 mi (4.0 km) soon after entering the Cowlitz River, but most continued downstream.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] After traveling 17 mi (27 km) further, an estimated 3,900,000 yd3 (3,000,000 m3) of material were injected into the Columbia River, reducing the river's depth by 25 ft (8 m) for a 4 mi (6 km) stretch.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The resulting 13 ft (4.0 m) river depth temporarily closed the busy channel to ocean-going freighters, costing Portland, Oregon, an estimated $5 million (equivalent to $15.9 million 2024).
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Ultimately, more than 65×10^6 yd3 (50×10^6 m3; 1.8×10^9 ft3) of sediment were dumped along the lower Cowlitz and Columbia Rivers.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The May 18, 1980, event was the most deadly and economically destructive volcanic eruption in the history of the contiguous United States.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] About 57 people were killed directly from the blast, and 200 houses, 47 bridges, 15 mi (24 km) of railways, and 185 mi (298 km) of highway were destroyed; two people were killed indirectly in accidents that resulted from poor visibility, and two more suffered fatal heart attacks from shoveling ash.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] President Jimmy Carter surveyed the damage, and said it looked more desolate than a moonscape.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A film crew was dropped by helicopter on Mount St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens on May 23 to document the destruction, but they quickly became lost, which the crew attributed to “magnetism in the ash and our contour maps made meaningless on the altered slopes”.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A second eruption occurred the next day (see below), but the crew survived and were rescued two days after that.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The eruption ejected more than 1 mi3 (4.2 km3) of material.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A quarter of that volume was fresh lava in the form of ash, pumice, and volcanic bombs, while the rest was fragmented, older rock.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The removal of the north side of the mountain (13% of the cone's volume) reduced Mount St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens' height by about 1,300 ft (400 m) and left a crater 1 to 2 mi (1.6 to 3.2 km) wide and 2,100 ft (640 m) deep with its north end open in a huge breach.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] More than 4,000,000,000 board feet (9,400,000 m3) of timber were damaged or destroyed, mainly by the lateral blast.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At least 25% of the destroyed timber was salvaged after September 1980.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Downwind of the volcano, in areas of thick ash accumulation, many agricultural crops, such as wheat, apples, potatoes, and alfalfa, were destroyed.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] As many as 1,500 elk and 5,000 deer were killed, and an estimated twelve million Chinook and Coho salmon fingerlings died when their hatcheries were destroyed.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Another estimated 40,000 young salmon were killed when they swam through turbine blades of hydroelectric generators after reservoir levels were lowered along the Lewis River to accommodate possible mudflows and flood waters.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens released 24 megatons TNT of thermal energy, seven of which were a direct result of the blast.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This is equivalent to 1,600 times the size of the atomic bomb dropped on Hiroshima.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In 2024, a study was conducted that provided an explanation for the observed phenomenon of an increase in the duration of the Lamb waves compared to the expected.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The death toll most commonly cited is 57, although two points of uncertainty remain.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The first point regards two officially listed victims, Paul Hiatt and Dale Thayer.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] They were reported missing after the explosion.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In the aftermath, investigators were able to locate individuals named Paul Hiatt and Dale Thayer who were alive and well.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] However, they were unable to determine who reported Hiatt missing, and the person who was listed as reporting Thayer missing claimed she was not the one who had done so.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Since the investigators could not thus verify that they were the same Hiatt and Thayer who were reported missing, the names remain listed among the presumed dead.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The second point regards three missing people who are not officially listed as victims: Robert Ruffle, Steven Whitsett, and Mark Melanson.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Cowlitz County Emergency Services Management lists them as "Possibly Missing — Not on [the official] List".
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] According to Melanson's brother, in October 1983, Cowlitz County officials told his family that Melanson "is believed [...] a victim of the May 18, 1980, eruption" and that after years of searching, the family eventually decided "he's buried in the ash".
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Taking these two points of uncertainty into consideration, the direct death toll could be as low as 55 or as high as 60.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] When combined with the four indirect victims (two dying from vehicle accidents due to poor visibility, and two dying from heart attacks triggered by shovelling ash) those numbers range from 59 to 64.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A year and a half after the eruption, the bodies of two young women, Marsha Anne Weatter and Katherine Jean Allen, 18 and 20 years old respectively, were discovered.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] They were believed to have been murdered six weeks before the eruption, rather than being killed by the events.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Backpacks belonging to them had been found in July 1980, but a layer of ash deposited by the eruption may have hidden the bodies, also preventing animals disturbing the remains.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] An autopsy showed they had each been shot once.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The murders of Weatter and Allen were later linked to serial killer Martin Lee Sanders.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The ash fall created some temporary major problems with transportation, sewage disposal, and water treatment systems.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Visibility was greatly decreased during the ash fall, closing many highways and roads.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Interstate 90 from Seattle to Spokane was closed for a week and a half.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Air travel was disrupted for between a few days and two weeks, as several airports in eastern Washington shut down because of ash accumulation and poor visibility.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Over a thousand commercial flights were cancelled following airport closures.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Fine-grained, gritty ash caused substantial problems for internal combustion engines and other mechanical and electrical equipment.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The ash contaminated oil systems, clogged air filters, and scratched moving surfaces.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Fine ash caused short circuits in electrical transformers, which in turn caused power blackouts.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Removing and disposing of the ash was a monumental task for some Eastern Washington communities.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] State and federal agencies estimated that over 2,400,000 yd3 (1,800,000 m3) of ash, equivalent to about 900,000 tons in weight, were removed from highways and airports in Washington.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The ash removal cost $2.2 million and took ten weeks in Yakima.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The need to remove ash quickly from transport routes and civil works dictated the selection of some disposal sites.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Some cities used old quarries and existing sanitary landfills; others created dump sites wherever expedient.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] To minimize wind reworking of ash dumps, the surfaces of some disposal sites were covered with topsoil and seeded with grass.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In Portland, the mayor eventually threatened businesses with fines if they failed to remove the ash from their parking lots.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A refined estimate of $1.1 billion ($3.5 billion in 2024) was determined in a study by the International Trade Commission at the request of the U.S.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A supplemental appropriation of $951 million for disaster relief was voted by Congress, of which the largest share went to the Small Business Administration, the U.S.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Army Corps of Engineers, and the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Also, indirect and intangible costs of the eruption were incurred.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Unemployment in the immediate region of Mount St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens rose 10-fold in the weeks immediately following the eruption, and then returned to near-normal levels once timber-salvaging and ash-cleanup operations were underway.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Only a small percentage of residents left the region because of lost jobs owing to the eruption.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Several months after May 18, a few residents reported suffering stress and emotional problems, though they had coped successfully during the crisis.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Counties in the region requested funding for mental-health programs to assist such people.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Initial public reaction to the May 18 eruption dealt a nearly crippling blow to tourism, an important industry in Washington.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Not only was tourism down in the Mount St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens–Gifford Pinchot National Forest area, but conventions, meetings and social gatherings also were cancelled or postponed at cities and resorts elsewhere in Washington and neighboring Oregon not affected by the eruption.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The adverse effect on tourism and conventioneering, however, proved only temporary.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens, perhaps because of its reawakening, has regained its appeal for tourists.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Forest Service and the State of Washington opened visitor centers and provided access for people to view the volcano's devastation.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens produced an additional five explosive eruptions between May and October 1980.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Through early 1990, at least 21 periods of eruptive activity occurred.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The volcano remains active, with smaller, dome-building eruptions continuing into 2008.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] An eruption occurred on May 25, 1980, at 2:30am that sent an ash column 9 mi (48,000 ft; 14 km) into the atmosphere.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The eruption was preceded by a sudden increase in earthquake activity, and occurred during a rainstorm.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Erratic wind from the storm carried ash from the eruption to the south and west, lightly dusting large parts of western Washington and Oregon.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Pyroclastic flows exited the northern breach and covered avalanche debris, lahars, and other pyroclastic flows deposited by the May 18 eruption.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At 7:05 pm on June 12, a plume of ash billowed 2.5 mi (4.0 km) above the volcano.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] At 9:09 pm, a much stronger explosion sent an ash column about 10 mi (16 km) skyward.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This event caused the Portland area, previously spared by wind direction, to be thinly coated with ash in the middle of the annual Rose Festival.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A dacite dome then oozed into existence on the crater floor, growing to a height of 200 ft (61 m) and a width of 1,200 ft (370 m) within a week.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A series of large explosions on July 22 broke more than a month of relative quiet.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The July eruptive episode was preceded by several days of measurable expansion of the summit area, heightened earthquake activity, and changed emission rates of sulfur dioxide and carbon dioxide.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The first hit at 5:14 pm as an ash column shot 10 mi (16 km) and was followed by a faster blast at 6:25 pm that pushed the ash column above its previous maximum height in just 7.5 minutes.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The final explosion started at 7:01 pm, and continued over two hours.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] When the relatively small amount of ash settled over eastern Washington, the dome built in June was gone.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Seismic activity and gas emission steadily increased in early August, and on August 7 at 4:26 pm an ash cloud slowly expanded 8 mi (13 km) into the sky.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Small pyroclastic flows came through the northern breach and a weaker outpouring of ash rose from the crater.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This continued until 10:32 pm, when a second large blast sent ash high into the air, proceeding due north.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A second dacite dome filled this vent a few days later.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Two months of repose were ended by an eruption lasting from October 16 to 18.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This event obliterated the second dome, sent ash ten miles in the air, and created small, red-hot pyroclastic flows.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] A third dome began to form within thirty minutes after the final explosion on October 18, and within a few days it was about 900 ft (270 m) wide and 130 ft (40 m) high.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] In spite of the dome growth next to it, a new glacier formed rapidly inside the crater.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] All of the post-1980 eruptions were quiet dome-building events, beginning with the December 27, 1980, to January 3, 1981, episode.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] By 1987 the third dome had grown to be more than 3,000 ft (910 m) wide and 800 ft (240 m) high.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Further eruptions occurred over a few months between 1989 and 1991.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The 2004–2008 volcanic activity of Mount St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Helens has been documented as a continuous eruption with a gradual extrusion of magma at the Mount St.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] Starting in October 2004, a gradual building of a new lava dome happened.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] The new dome did not rise above the crater created by the 1980 eruption.
[src:explosion/1980-eruption-of-mount-st-helens] This activity lasted until January 2008.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] On 21 June 1988, a large fire and explosion engulfed the BDH chemical plant in Poole, Dorset, England.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] 3,500 people were evacuated from the town centre in the biggest peacetime evacuation in the UK since World War II.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] Despite the intensity of the explosion, nobody was killed or seriously injured.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] British Drug Houses (BDH) had operated in Poole for 40 years.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] The plant at West Quay Road was constructed in 1982.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] At about 7:30 pm, emergency services were called to a fire at an industrial unit on West Quay Road in Poole.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] The warehouse was operated by BDH and stood adjacent to the Port of Poole, and close to residential and commercial areas in Old Poole.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] The fire was discovered in an oxidising storeroom, and it had spread to the adjacent area containing flammable liquids.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] There were flames up to 100 ft (30 m) high and flaming drums full of liquids were sent into the air and rained down on neighbouring streets.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] Missiles from the fire spread 50 m (150 ft), and there was off-site damage to 100 m (350 ft) away.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] A fireball was witnessed and a plume of yellow-brown smoke was seen rising over Poole Old Town.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] An evacuation began at 7:45 pm, affecting a 1 square mile (2.6 km2) radius in Poole Town Centre.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] Nearby tower blocks were emptied, and terraced streets were searched.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] People were sent to the Arts Centre, Sports Centre and the Arndale Centre (now Dolphin Shopping Centre).
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] The evacuation was organised by Station Manager Gordon Hughes.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] In November 1988, he became only the second recipient of the Chief Officer's Commendation.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] Fourteen people were taken to Poole General Hospital.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] Local residents were not allowed to return to their homes until 5:30 am the next day.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] The Health and Safety Executive, on the scene that morning, said the devastation would make an investigation of the cause virtually impossible.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] Street furniture and traffic lights had melted and windows were smashed.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] The smoke was analysed to have contained hydrogen chloride.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] Pollution of watercourses, including Poole Harbour, was also of concern.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] Authorities said that luck had kept the injuries minor, as barrels containing cyanide did not explode and the wind blew the toxic smoke offshore.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] Member of Parliament for Poole, John Ward asked the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Employment, Patrick Nicholls, to set up a public inquiry into the incident.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] The minister confirmed that the Health and Safety Executive would carry out a full investigation into the cause of the fire.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] The results of the investigation were published and publicised at a press conference held on 17 October 1988.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] The minister also confirmed that the BDH facilities at West Quay Road had been inspected 15 times between 1979 and 1988.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] In 1997, BDH closed the West Quay Road plant and half of its local workforce was made redundant.
[src:explosion/1988-poole-explosion] The factory was pulled down and the land is now occupied by Poole Lifeboat Station, other buildings making up the Royal National Lifeboat Institution headquarters, and the Lifeboat College, which opened in 2004.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The **1991 eruption of Mount Pinatubo** in the Philippines' Luzon Volcanic Arc was the second-largest volcanic eruption of the 20th century, behind only the 1912 eruption of Novarupta in Alaska.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Eruptive activity began on April 2 as a series of phreatic explosions from a fissure that opened on the north side of Mount Pinatubo.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Seismographs were set up and began monitoring the volcano for earthquakes.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In late May, the number of seismic events under the volcano fluctuated from day-to-day.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Beginning June 6, a swarm of progressively shallower earthquakes accompanied by inflationary tilt on the upper east flank of the mountain, culminated in the extrusion of a small lava dome.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] On June 12, the volcano's first spectacular eruption sent an ash column 19 km (12 mi) into the atmosphere.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Additional explosions occurred overnight and the morning of June 13.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Seismic activity during this period became intense.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] When even more highly gas-charged magma reached Pinatubo's surface on June 15, the volcano exploded, sending an ash cloud 40 km (25 mi) into the atmosphere.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Volcanic ash and pumice blanketed the countryside.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Huge pyroclastic flows roared down the flanks of Pinatubo, filling once-deep valleys with fresh volcanic deposits as much as 200 m (660 ft) thick.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The eruption removed so much magma and rock from beneath the volcano that the summit collapsed to form a small caldera 2.5 km (1.6 mi) across.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Fine ash from the eruption fell as far away as the Indian Ocean and satellites tracked the ash cloud as it traveled several times around the globe.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] At least 16 commercial jets inadvertently flew through the drifting ash cloud, sustaining about $100 million in damage.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] With the ashfall came darkness and the sounds of lahars rumbling down nearby river valleys.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Several smaller lahars washed through the Clark Air Base, flowing across the base in enormously powerful sheets, slamming into buildings and scattering cars.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Nearly every bridge within 30 km (19 mi) of Mount Pinatubo was destroyed.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Several lowland towns were flooded or partially buried in mud.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] More than 840 people were killed from the collapse of roofs under wet heavy ash and several more were injured.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Rain continued to create hazards over the next several years, as the volcanic deposits were remobilized into secondary mudflows.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Damage to bridges, irrigation-canal systems, roads, cropland, and urban areas occurred in the wake of each significant rainfall.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Many more people were affected for much longer by rain-induced lahars than by the eruption itself.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] On July 16, 1990, a magnitude 7.8 earthquake struck northern Central Luzon and the Cordilleras.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] This was the largest earthquake recorded in 1990.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Its epicenter was in the municipality of Rizal, Nueva Ecija, about 100 km (62 mi) northeast of Pinatubo, and faulted northwest–southeast through three provinces.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] It also followed the Philippine Fault System west as far as Baguio, which was devastated, and is located about 80 km (50 mi) north-northeast of Pinatubo, leading volcanologists to speculate that it might ultimately have triggered the 1991 eruption, although this is impossible to prove conclusively.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Two weeks after the earthquake, local residents reported steam coming from the volcano, but scientists who visited there in response found only small rockslides rather than any pre-eruptive activity.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] On March 15, 1991, a succession of earthquakes were felt by villagers on the northwestern side of the volcano.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Further earthquakes of increasing intensity were felt over the next two weeks, and it became clear some kind of volcanic activity was likely.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] On April 2, the volcano woke up, with phreatic eruptions occurring near the summit along a 1.5 km (0.93 mi) long fissure.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Over the next few weeks, small eruptions continued, dusting the surrounding areas with volcanic ash.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Seismographs recorded hundreds of small earthquakes every day.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Scientists immediately installed monitoring equipment and analyzed the volcano for clues as to its previous eruptive history.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Radiocarbon dating of charcoal found in old volcanic deposits revealed the last three major explosive eruption periods in recent millennia, about 5500, 3500 and 500 years ago.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Geological mapping showed that much of the surrounding plains were formed by lahar flood deposits from previous eruptions.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Volcanic activity increased throughout May.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Measurements of sulfur dioxide emissions showed a rapid increase from 500 t (550 short tons) per day by May 13 to 5,000 t (5,500 short tons) per day by May 28.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] This implied that there was a rising column of fresh magma beneath the volcano.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] After May 28, the amount of SO 2 being emitted decreased substantially, raising fears that the degassing of the magma had been blocked somehow, leading to a pressure build-up in the magma chamber and a high likelihood of violent explosive eruptions.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In early June, tiltmeter measurements had shown that the volcano was gradually inflating, evidently due to fast-growing amounts of magma filling the reservoir beneath the summit.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] At the same time, seismic activity, previously concentrated at a depth of a few kilometers below a point about 5 kilometres (3.1 mi) northwest of the summit, shifted to shallow depths just below the summit.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Such an event is a precursor of volcano tectonic earthquakes.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Given all the signs that a very large eruption was imminent, the Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology – assisted by the United States Geological Survey – worked to convince local inhabitants of the high severity of the threat.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] A false warning might have led to cynicism about any later warnings, but delaying a warning until an eruption began might lead to thousands of deaths, so the volcanologists were under some pressure to deliver a timely and accurate assessment of the volcanic risk.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The 10 km (6.2 mi) and 10–20 km (6.2–12.4 mi) zones had a total population of about 40,000 inhabitants, while some more 331,000 inhabitants lived in the 20–40 km (12–25 mi) zone.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Five stages of volcanic alert were defined, from level 1 (low level seismic disturbances) up to level 5 (major eruption in progress).
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Daily alerts were issued stating the alert level and associated danger area, and the information was announced in major regional and national newspapers, on radio and television stations, by nongovernmental organizations (NGOs) and directly to the endangered inhabitants.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Many of the Aetas who lived on the slopes of the volcano left their villages of their own volition when the first blasts began in April, gathering in a village about 12 kilometres (7.5 mi) from the summit.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] They moved to increasingly distant settlements as the eruptions escalated, some Aetas moving up to nine times in the two months before the colossal eruption.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The first formal evacuations were ordered for the 10 km (6.2 mi) zone on April 7.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Evacuation of the 10–20 km (6.2–12.4 mi) zone was ordered when a level 4 alert was issued on June 7.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] A level 5 alert triggered evacuation of the 20–40 km (12–25 mi) zone on June 13, and in all some 60,000 people had left the area within 30 kilometres (19 mi) of the volcano before June 15.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Most people temporarily relocated to Metro Manila, with some 30,000 using the Amoranto Velodrome in Quezon City as an evacuee camp.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] On June 7, the first magmatic eruptions took place with the formation of a lava dome at the summit of the volcano.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The dome grew substantially over the next five days, reaching a maximum diameter of about 200 m (660 ft) and a height of 40 m (130 ft).
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] A small blast at 03:41 on June 12 marked the beginning of a new, more violent phase of the eruption.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] A few hours later the same day, massive blasts lasting about half an hour generated big eruption columns, which quickly reached heights of over 19 kilometres (12 mi) and which generated large pyroclastic surges extending up to four kilometres (2.5 mi) from the summit in some river valleys.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] One witness at Subic Bay described the explosion as 'hitting him as a whoosh of pressure'.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Fourteen hours later, a 15-minute blast hurled volcanic matter to heights of 24 km (15 mi).
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Friction in the up-rushing ash column generated abundant volcanic lightning.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] A third large eruption began at 08:41 on June 13, after an intense swarm of small earthquakes over the previous two hours.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] It lasted about five minutes, and the eruption column once again reached 24 km (15 mi).
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] After three hours of quiet, seismic activity began, growing more and more intense over the next twenty-four hours, until a three-minute eruptive blast generated a 21 km (13 mi) high eruption column at 13:09 on June 14.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Tephra fall from these four large eruptions was extensive to the southwest of the volcano.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Two hours after the last of these four explosions, a series of eruptions began which lasted for the next twenty-four hours, and which saw the production of much larger pyroclastic flows and surges which travelled several kilometres down river valleys on the flanks of the volcano.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In total, almost 400 km2 (150 sq mi) of land was buried by pyroclastic density currents which travelled in all directions, and reached at least 12 km (7.5 mi), and as far as 16 km (9.9 mi), from the volcano.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The land closest to the eruption was eroded by the pyroclastic currents, which did not leave much deposit there.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Dacite was the dominant igneous rock making up the tephra in these eruptions and in the following climactic event.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The most abundant phenocryst minerals were hornblende and plagioclase, but an unusual phenocryst mineral was also present – the calcium sulfate called anhydrite.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The dacite magma was more oxidized than most magmas, and the sulfur-rich nature of the eruption was probably causally related to the redox state.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The final, climactic eruption of Mount Pinatubo began at 13:42 on June 15.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] It caused numerous major earthquakes due to the collapse of the summit and the creation of a caldera 2.5 km (1.6 mi) in diameter, reducing the peak from 1,745 m (5,725 ft) to 1,486 m (4,875 ft).
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] All the seismographs close to Clark Air Base had been rendered completely inoperative by 14:30, mostly by super-massive pyroclastic surges.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Intense atmospheric pressure variation was also recorded.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] On the same day, Typhoon Yunya, locally named Diding, struck the island, with its center passing about 75 km (47 mi) north of the volcano.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The typhoon rains mostly obscured the eruption, but measurements showed that ash was ejected to a height of 34 km (21 mi) by the most violent phase of the eruption, which lasted about three hours.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Pyroclastic surges poured from the summit, reaching as far as 16 km (9.9 mi) away from their origin point.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Typhoon rains and flooding, mixed with the ash deposits, caused a messy rain of mud and massive lahars.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The volcanic column from the crater covered an area of some 125,000 km2 (48,000 sq mi), bringing total darkness to much of Central Luzon for 36 hours.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Almost all of the island received some wet ash fall, which formed a heavy, rain-saturated snow-like blanket.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Tephra fell over most of the South China Sea and ash falls were recorded as far away as Vietnam, Cambodia, Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Twelve days after the first magmatic eruptions of June 3, on June 15, 1991, by about 22:30, and about nine hours after the onset of the most recent climactic phase, atmospheric pressure waves had decreased to the pre-eruption levels.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] No seismic records were available at this time, but volcanologists believe 22:30 marked the end of the climactic eruption.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Vast quantities of light and heavy metal minerals were brought to the surface.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] At least 16 commercial aircraft had damaging in-flight encounters with the ash cloud ejected by the June 15 eruption, and many grounded aircraft were also significantly damaged.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In-flight encounters caused loss of power to one engine on two different aircraft.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Ten engines were damaged and replaced, including all three engines of one DC-10.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Longer-term damage to aircraft and engines was reported, including accumulation of sulfate deposits on engines.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The eruption also irreparably damaged the Philippine Air Force's recently retired fleet of Vought F-8s, as these were in open storage at Basa Air Base at the time.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The 1991 eruption rated 6 on the Volcanic Explosivity Index and came some 450–500 years after the volcano's last known eruptive activity.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The eruption ejected over 10 km3 (2.4 cu mi) of material, making it the largest eruption of the 20th century since that of Novarupta in 1912 and ten times larger than the 1980 eruption of Mount St.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Ejected material such as tephra fallout and pyroclastic flow deposits are much less dense than magma, and the volume of ejected material was equivalent to about five cubic kilometres (1.2 cu mi) of unerupted material.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Thermal energy released during the eruption was equal to 70 megatons of TNT.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The former summit of the volcano was obliterated and replaced by a caldera 2.5 km (1.6 mi) wide.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The highest point on the caldera rim now stood 1,485 m (4,872 ft) above sea level, some 260 m (850 ft) lower than the pre-eruption summit.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The eruption killed 847 people, mostly by roofs collapsing under a load of accumulated volcanic matter, a hazard amplified by the simultaneous arrival of Typhoon Yunya.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The evacuation in the days before the eruption certainly saved tens of thousands of lives, and has been hailed as a great success for volcanology and eruption prediction.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] After the eruption, about 500,000 people continue to live within 40 km (25 mi) of the volcano, with population centers including the 150,000 in Angeles City and 30,000 at Clark Freeport Zone.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Many reforestation projects were destroyed in the eruption, with a total area of 150 km2 (58 sq mi; 37,000 acres) valued at 125 million pesos destroyed.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Agriculture was heavily disrupted, with 800 km2 (310 sq mi; 200,000 acres) of rice-growing farmland destroyed, and almost 800,000 head of livestock and poultry killed, destroying the livelihoods of thousands of farmers.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The cost to agriculture of eruption effects was estimated to be 1.5 billion pesos.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Many farmers near Pinatubo began growing quick-ripening crops such as peanuts, cassava, and sweet potatoes, which could be harvested before the threat of lahar floods during the late summer rainy season.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In total, 364 communities and 2.1 million people were affected by the eruption, with livelihoods and houses being damaged and destroyed.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] More than 8,000 houses were destroyed, and a further 73,000 were damaged.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In addition to the severe damage sustained by these communities, roads and communications were damaged or destroyed by pyroclastic surges and lahar floods throughout the areas surrounding the volcano.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Total losses in 1991 and 1992 alone were estimated at 10.6 and 1.2 billion pesos respectively, including damage to public infrastructure estimated at 3.8 billion pesos (c.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] US$92 million, or $175 million today, adjusted for inflation).
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] School classes for thousands of children was temporarily suspended by the destruction of schools in the eruption.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The eruption of Pinatubo severely hampered the economic development of the surrounding areas.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The gross regional domestic product of the Pinatubo area accounted for about 10% of the total Philippine gross domestic product.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The GRDP had been growing at 5% annually before the eruption but fell by more than 3% from 1990 to 1991.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In 1991, damage to crops and property was estimated at $374 million (or $711 million today), to which continuing lahar floods added a further $69 million (or $127 million today) in 1992.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In total, 42 percent of the cropland around the volcano was affected by more lahar floods, dealing a severe blow to the agricultural economy in the region.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Since the eruption, each heavy rain has brought massive lahars from the volcano, displacing thousands of people and inflicting extensive damage to buildings and infrastructure costing billions to repair.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Funds were spent constructing dikes and dams to control post-eruption lahar flows.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Several important river systems stem from Mount Pinatubo, the major rivers being the Tarlac, Abacan, Pasig-Potrero, Sta.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Lucia, Bucao, Santo Tomas, Maloma, Tanguay, Ashley and Kileng rivers.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Before the eruption, these river systems were important ecosystems, but the eruption filled many valleys with deep pyroclastic deposits.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Since 1991, the rivers have been clogged with sediment, and the valleys have seen frequent lahars which continued for years after the eruption.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Studies show that the river systems will take decades to recover from the June 1991 eruption.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] On September 3, 1995, a lahar buried San Guillermo Parish Church in Bacolor, Pampanga to half its 12 metres (39 ft) height.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The United States Air Force initiated a massive airlift effort to evacuate American service members and their families from the two affected bases during and immediately following the eruption, named Operation Fiery Vigil.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The first sea-based evacuations departed June 16 from Alava Wharf, Naval Base Subic Bay aboard USS *Rodney M.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Davis*, USS *Curts*, and USS *Arkansas*, all of whom were in port or who had made port immediately after the initial plume of June 12.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Each made two passages from Subic Bay transporting evacuees to Cebu City, Visayas, for subsequent transport by USAF units to Andersen AFB, Guam.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Additional maritime evacuations began several days later with the arrival of the USS *Abraham Lincoln* battle group, USS *Midway*, and USS *Peleliu*.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Most personnel were initially relocated to Guam, Okinawa and the U.S. state of Hawaii, although some returned to the continental United States.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Clark Air Base was ultimately abandoned by the United States military because of the eruption, and Subic Bay reverted to Philippine control in November 1992 following the breakdown of lease negotiations and the expiration of the Military Bases Agreement of 1947.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The powerful eruption of such an enormous volume of lava and ash injected significant quantities of aerosols and dust into the stratosphere.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Sulfur dioxide oxidized in the atmosphere to produce a haze of sulfuric acid droplets, which gradually spread throughout the stratosphere over the year following the eruption.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The injection of aerosols into the stratosphere is thought to have been the largest since the 1883 eruption of Krakatoa, with a total mass of SO 2 of about 17,000,000 t (19,000,000 short tons) being injected – the largest volume ever recorded by modern instruments (see chart and figure).
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] This very large stratospheric injection resulted in a reduction in the normal amount of sunlight reaching the Earth's surface by roughly 10% (see figure).
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] A volcanic cooling ensued, leading to a decrease in Northern Hemisphere average temperatures of 0.5–0.6 °C (0.9–1.1 °F) and a global decrease of about 0.4 °C (0.7 °F).
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The 1991 eruption also caused the "Summer that Wasn't" in 1992.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The extremity of this volcanic cooling has been called into question by some, however, with a more conservative estimate of a 0.2 °C decrease in global temperatures for 13 months also being given.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] At the same time, the temperature in the stratosphere rose to several degrees higher than normal, due to the absorption of radiation by the aerosol.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The stratospheric cloud from the eruption persisted in the atmosphere for three years.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The eruption, while not directly responsible, may have played a part in the formation of the 1991 Perfect Storm, 1991 Halloween blizzard and 1993 Storm of the Century.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The eruption had a significant effect on ozone levels in the atmosphere, causing a large increase in the destruction rate of ozone.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Ozone levels at middle latitudes reached their lowest recorded levels, while in the Southern Hemisphere winter of 1992, the ozone hole over Antarctica reached its largest ever size until then, with the fastest recorded ozone depletion rates.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The eruption of Mount Hudson in Chile in August 1991 also contributed to southern hemisphere ozone destruction, with measurements showing a sharp decrease in ozone levels at the tropopause when the aerosol clouds from Pinatubo and Hudson arrived.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Another noticeable effect of the dust in the atmosphere was the appearance of lunar eclipses.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Normally even at mid-eclipse, the Moon is still visible although much dimmed, whereas in the year following the Pinatubo eruption, the Moon was hardly visible at all during eclipses, due to much greater absorption of sunlight by dust in the atmosphere.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] It has also been suggested that excess cloud condensation nuclei from the eruption were responsible for the "Great Flood of 1993" in the Midwestern United States.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The Aeta people were the hardest hit by the eruption.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] After the areas surrounding the volcano were declared safe, many Aetas returned to their old villages only to find them destroyed by pyroclastic and lahar deposits.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Some were able to return to their former way of life, but most moved instead to government-organized resettlement areas.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Conditions on these were poor, with each family receiving only small plots of land not ideal for growing crops.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Many Aeta found casual labor working for lowland farmers, and overall Aeta society became much more fragmented, and reliant on and integrated with lowland culture.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The government implemented several rehabilitative and reconstructive programs.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Projects that will help deal with the aftermath brought about by lahar were also implemented.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Among these is the construction of mega dikes.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Moreover, to hasten the implementation of the basic services for the afflicted, private sectors, including the NGOs, took part in offering relief.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] They provided support and coordinated on the services that were deemed lacking from the side of the government.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The Asian Disaster Reduction Center was founded in Kobe, Hyogo prefecture, in 1998, with a mission to improve disaster resilience of its fifty member countries, to build safe communities, and to create a society where there is an achievable sustainable development.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The center works to build and establish networks among countries through many programs such as personnel exchanges in this field.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] After the eruption, many of the homes were destroyed and many of the areas affected by lahar were deemed uninhabitable.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] There was need to resettle the people particularly the Aetas and lowlanders.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Resettlement for these two needs to take into consideration the factors of their socio-cultural and socioeconomic differences.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Faced with the destruction of many of the farmlands and the displacement of farmers and other workers the government had to search for a long-term solution to address the issue.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Agricultural-based industries were also greatly affected.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The closure of Clark Air base also raised an issue of finding short-term livelihoods and the need to use the base lands to cushion the repercussions of the worker's displacement.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The destruction brought about by the incident pressured social service sectors to continue their efforts in assisting in terms of health, social welfare, and education.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The services offered are not limited to the victims within the evacuation centers but also offered to the others affected.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] While the event happened during the opening of a school year, classes were needed to be pushed back as school facilities were destroyed.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Providing resettlement for the evacuees was also a major concern.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Social services were also provided in the prospective resettlement areas to prepare the victims when settling down.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Destruction of many infrastructures was mostly due to the wet ash after the explosion.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The region's roads, bridges, public buildings, facilities, communication, and structures for river and flood control were some of the great concerns of the government.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] A need to establish measures for the flash floods and the threat caused by lahar also became an imperative demand to the government.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The aftereffects of the eruption damaged not only man-made structures but also farmlands, forestlands, and watersheds.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] River systems and the overall environment of the affected region are also heavily damaged by the heavy lahar flow.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] To address this careful replanning of the land area region is necessary.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] This event showed the need to engage in scientific studies to reassess the current policies and knowledge on areas with risk of eruption.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Studies should also be allocated on a possible application for the ash fall for industrial and commercial purposes.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The significance of this concern affects both the government and private sectors.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Even before the Philippine government officially appealed for international assistance, the Office of U.S.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Foreign Disaster Assistance (USAID/OFDA) shipped shelter material for victims of the floods and lahars in late July 1992.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In the following month, they provided $375 000 to be used for relief and rehabilitation projects.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The Department of Social Welfare and Development had claimed during an informal donors' meeting with representatives from mostly international agencies who compose the donor community that the national government was still well-equipped and had sufficient resources to aid the victims.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] The UN-Disaster Management Team (DMT) and the United Nations' Department of Humanitarian Affairs/United Nations Disaster Relief Organization (DHA/UNDRO) continued cooperating with the national government to monitor the situation and formulate ideas for further assistance.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] It was not until then-President Fidel V.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Ramos had declared the affected provinces and areas to be in a state of emergency that the national government officially requested for international assistance and for aid in projects for rehabilitation and relief provisions in the aforementioned areas.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In response to this, the DHA/UNDRO reached out to the international community to respond to the appeal, and continued their operations, coordinating with the government.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] Relief assistance from these organizations and countries were in the form of either cash donation or relief items such as food packs, medicines, and shelter materials.
[src:explosion/1991-eruption-of-mount-pinatubo] In Termination Shock, Pinatubo is a somewhat prominent plot point due to the long-term environmental impact of releasing sulfur dioxide inspiring the Geoengineering project in the novel.
[src:explosion/explosion] An **explosion** is a rapid expansion in volume of a given amount of matter associated with an extreme outward release of energy, usually with the generation of high temperatures and release of high-pressure gases.
[src:explosion/explosion] Explosions may also be generated by a slower expansion that would normally not be forceful, but is not allowed to expand, so that when whatever is containing the expansion is broken by the pressure that builds as the matter inside tries to expand, the matter expands forcefully.
[src:explosion/explosion] An example of this is a volcanic eruption created by the expansion of magma in a magma chamber as it rises to the surface.
[src:explosion/explosion] Supersonic explosions created by high explosives are known as detonations and travel through shock waves.
[src:explosion/explosion] Subsonic explosions are created by low explosives through a slower combustion process known as deflagration.
[src:explosion/explosion] For an explosion to occur, there must be a rapid, forceful expansion of matter.
[src:explosion/explosion] There are numerous ways this can happen, both naturally and artificially, such as volcanic eruptions, or two objects striking each other at very high speeds, as in an impact event.
[src:explosion/explosion] Explosive volcanic eruptions occur when magma rises from below, it has dissolved gas in it.
[src:explosion/explosion] The reduction of pressure as the magma rises causes the gas to bubble out of solution, resulting in a rapid increase in volume, however the size of the magma chamber remains the same.
[src:explosion/explosion] This results in pressure buildup that eventually leads to an explosive eruption.
[src:explosion/explosion] Explosions can also occur outside of Earth in the universe in events such as supernovae, or, more commonly, stellar flares.
[src:explosion/explosion] Humans are also able to create explosions through the use of explosives, or through nuclear fission or fusion, as in a nuclear weapon.
[src:explosion/explosion] Explosions frequently occur during bushfires in eucalyptus forests where the volatile oils in the tree tops suddenly combust.
[src:explosion/explosion] Among the largest known explosions in the universe are supernovae, which occur after the end of life of some types of stars.
[src:explosion/explosion] Solar flares are an example of common, much less energetic, explosions on the Sun, and presumably on most other stars as well.
[src:explosion/explosion] The energy source for solar flare activity comes from the tangling of magnetic field lines resulting from the rotation of the Sun's conductive plasma.
[src:explosion/explosion] Another type of large astronomical explosion occurs when a meteoroid or an asteroid impacts the surface of another object, or explodes in its atmosphere, such as a planet.
[src:explosion/explosion] This occurs because the two objects are moving at very high speed relative to each other (a minimum of 11.2 kilometres per second (7.0 mi/s) for an Earth impacting body).
[src:explosion/explosion] For example, the Tunguska event of 1908 is believed to have resulted from a meteor air burst.
[src:explosion/explosion] Black hole mergers, likely involving binary black hole systems, are capable of radiating many solar masses of energy into the universe in a fraction of a second, in the form of gravitational waves.
[src:explosion/explosion] This is capable of transmitting ordinary energy and destructive forces to nearby objects, but in the vastness of space, nearby objects are rare.
[src:explosion/explosion] The gravitational wave observed on 21 May 2019, known as GW190521, produced a merger signal of about 100 ms duration, during which time is it estimated to have radiated away nine solar masses in the form of gravitational energy.
[src:explosion/explosion] The most common artificial explosives are chemical explosives, usually involving a rapid and violent oxidation reaction that produces large amounts of hot gas.
[src:explosion/explosion] Gunpowder was the first explosive to be invented and put to use.
[src:explosion/explosion] Other notable early developments in chemical explosive technology were Frederick Augustus Abel's development of nitrocellulose in 1865 and Alfred Nobel's invention of dynamite in 1866.
[src:explosion/explosion] Chemical explosions (both intentional and accidental) are often initiated by an electric spark or flame in the presence of oxygen.
[src:explosion/explosion] Accidental explosions may occur in fuel tanks, rocket engines, etc.
[src:explosion/explosion] Chemical reactions that cause explosions are typically either unimolecular decomposition reactions or multi-molecular reduction-oxidation (redox) reactions.
[src:explosion/explosion] A high current electrical fault can create an "electrical explosion" by forming a high-energy electrical arc which rapidly vaporizes metal and insulation material.
[src:explosion/explosion] This arc flash hazard is a danger to people working on energized switchgear.
[src:explosion/explosion] Excessive magnetic pressure within an ultra-strong electromagnet can cause a *magnetic explosion*.
[src:explosion/explosion] Strictly a physical process, as opposed to chemical or nuclear, e.g., the bursting of a sealed or partially sealed container under internal pressure is often referred to as an explosion.
[src:explosion/explosion] Examples include an overheated boiler or a simple tin can of beans tossed into a fire.
[src:explosion/explosion] Boiling liquid expanding vapor explosions are one type of mechanical explosion that can occur when a vessel containing a pressurized liquid is ruptured, causing a rapid increase in volume as the liquid evaporates.
[src:explosion/explosion] Note that the contents of the container may cause a subsequent chemical explosion, the effects of which can be dramatically more serious, such as a propane tank in the midst of a fire.
[src:explosion/explosion] In such a case, to the effects of the mechanical explosion when the tank fails are added the effects from the explosion resulting from the released (initially liquid and then almost instantaneously gaseous) propane in the presence of an ignition source.
[src:explosion/explosion] For this reason, emergency workers often differentiate between the two events.
[src:explosion/explosion] In addition to stellar nuclear explosions, a nuclear weapon is a type of explosive weapon that derives its destructive force from nuclear fission or from a combination of fission and fusion.
[src:explosion/explosion] As a result, even a nuclear weapon with a small yield is significantly more powerful than the largest conventional explosives available, with a single weapon capable of completely destroying an entire city.
[src:explosion/explosion] Explosive force is released in a direction perpendicular to the surface of the explosive.
[src:explosion/explosion] If a grenade is in mid air during the explosion, the direction of the blast will be 360°.
[src:explosion/explosion] In contrast, in a shaped charge the explosive forces are focused to produce a greater local explosion; shaped charges are often used by military to breach doors or walls.
[src:explosion/explosion] The speed of the reaction is what distinguishes an explosive reaction from an ordinary combustion reaction.
[src:explosion/explosion] Unless the reaction occurs very rapidly, the thermally expanding gases will be moderately dissipated in the medium, with no large differential in pressure and no explosion.
[src:explosion/explosion] As a wood fire burns in a fireplace, for example, there certainly is the evolution of heat and the formation of gases, but neither is liberated rapidly enough to build up a sudden substantial pressure differential and then cause an explosion.
[src:explosion/explosion] This can be likened to the difference between the energy discharge of a battery, which is slow, and that of a flash capacitor like that in a camera flash, which releases its energy all at once.
[src:explosion/explosion] The generation of heat in large quantities accompanies most explosive chemical reactions.
[src:explosion/explosion] The exceptions are called entropic explosives and include organic peroxides such as acetone peroxide.
[src:explosion/explosion] It is the rapid liberation of heat that causes the gaseous products of most explosive reactions to expand and generate high pressures.
[src:explosion/explosion] This rapid generation of high pressures of the released gas constitutes the explosion.
[src:explosion/explosion] The liberation of heat with insufficient rapidity will not cause an explosion.
[src:explosion/explosion] For example, although a unit mass of coal yields five times as much heat as a unit mass of nitroglycerin, the coal cannot be used as an explosive (except in the form of coal dust) because the rate at which it yields this heat is quite slow.
[src:explosion/explosion] In fact, a substance that burns less rapidly (*i.e.* slow combustion) may actually evolve more total heat than an explosive that detonates rapidly (*i.e.* fast combustion).
[src:explosion/explosion] See Heat of Combustion for a more thorough treatment of this topic.
[src:explosion/explosion] When a chemical compound is formed from its constituents, heat may either be absorbed or released.
[src:explosion/explosion] The quantity of heat absorbed or given off during transformation is called the heat of formation.
[src:explosion/explosion] Heats of formations for solids and gases found in explosive reactions have been determined for a temperature of 25 °C and atmospheric pressure, and are normally given in units of kilojoules per gram-molecule.
[src:explosion/explosion] A positive value indicates that heat is absorbed during the formation of the compound from its elements; such a reaction is called an endothermic reaction.
[src:explosion/explosion] In explosive technology only materials that are exothermic—that have a net liberation of heat and have a negative heat of formation—are of interest.
[src:explosion/explosion] Reaction heat is measured under conditions either of constant pressure or constant volume.
[src:explosion/explosion] A chemical explosive is a compound or mixture which, upon the application of heat or shock, decomposes or rearranges with extreme rapidity, yielding much gas and heat.
[src:explosion/explosion] Many substances not ordinarily classed as explosives may do one, or even two, of these things.
[src:explosion/explosion] A reaction must be capable of being initiated by the application of shock, heat, or a catalyst (in the case of some explosive chemical reactions) to a small portion of the mass of the explosive material.
[src:explosion/explosion] A material in which the first three factors exist cannot be accepted as an explosive unless the reaction can be made to occur when needed.
[src:explosion/explosion] Fragmentation is the accumulation and projection of particles as the result of a high explosives detonation.
[src:explosion/explosion] High velocity, low angle fragments can travel hundreds of metres with enough energy to initiate other surrounding high explosive items, injure or kill personnel, and/or damage vehicles or structures.
[src:explosion/explosion] In aerospace engineering, the term rapid unscheduled/unplanned disassembly is humorously used as a euphemism for the explosion of an aircraft or spacecraft.
[src:explosion/explosion] It was used by Elon Musk in 2015 after a failure of its Falcon 9 first-stage landing mechanism after it lost control just before landing.
[src:explosion/explosion] Classical Latin *explōdō* means "to hiss a bad actor off the stage", "to drive an actor off the stage by making noise", from *ex-* ("out") + *plaudō* ("to clap; to applaud").
